(45, 'Software Defined Networking', ' SDN is also one thing that is a vast improvement in the network industry. SDN improves the network scalability and with the more and more data and information is moving to the clouds, it is a need to make them all affordable and available with great accu', 'SDN, Software Defined Networking, What is Software Defined Networking, Why do network Industry need SDN ', 'Gagandeep Singh', 'What is Software Defined Networking or SDN and Why do network Industry need SDN ?', 'what-is-software-defined-networking-or-sdn-and-why-do-network-industry-need-sdn-', '<h1>\r\n	Software Defined Networking</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n	IT world is always consistent with its change, be it in server administration, database administration, programming, or network industry. Last decade or so has seen the rise of new technologies in the likes of Cloud Computing, Automation, Big Data, Software Defined Networking. Job roles are changing and so is the requirements. Our industry is moving at very rapid pace and now totally uses business driven approach. SDN is also one thing that is a vast improvement in the network industry. SDN improves the network scalability and with the more and more data and information is moving to the clouds, it is a need to make them all affordable and available with great accuracy and SDN is the thing made for it. Big names in Network Industries like Cisco, Juniper etc, Large IT Companies like IBM, Dell, HP etc and some new companies like Big Switch Networks etc are digging in to the SDN revolution, as according to&nbsp;<a href="https://www.idc.com/getdoc.jsp?containerId=prUS25052314">IDC, SDN will become $8 billion industry in 2018</a>. So what actually is SDN is the big question ?</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/6d218-iowiki-software-defined-networking-sdn-image-1.jpg"><img alt="iowiki-software-defined-networking-sdn" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/6d218-iowiki-software-defined-networking-sdn-image-1.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 259px; float: left; margin: 20px;" /></a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	SDN is the physical separation of Control Plane from the Forwading Plane. According the Open Networking Foundation(ONF), Software Defined Networking is an emerging architecture which is dynamic, manageable , cost-effective and adaptable that makes it ideal for today&rsquo;s high bandwidth and dynamic nature type applications. SDN decouples the control and forwarding plane which allows the network control to be totally programmable with the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted for network services and applications. The SDN architecture is :</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Directly Programmable</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Agile</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Centrally Managed</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Programmatically Configured</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Open Standards Based</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Why is there a need erupts for a new architecture ?</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Changing traffic patterns</strong>: Applications that commonly access geographically distributed databases and servers through public and private clouds require extremely flexible traffic management and access to bandwidth on demand.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>The &ldquo;consumerization of IT&rdquo;</strong>: The&nbsp;<strong>Bring Your Own Device (BYOD)</strong>trend requires networks that are both flexible and secure.&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>The rise of cloud services</strong>: Users expect on-demand access to applications, infrastructure, and other IT resources and with the cloud is still in its developing phase, it will only rise with time.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>&ldquo;Big data&rdquo; means more bandwidth</strong>: Handling today&rsquo;s mega datasets requires massive parallel processing that is fueling a constant demand for additional capacity and any-to-any connectivity.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	In order to meet the requirements that are posed by current evolving trends, network designers find themselves constrained by the limitations of current networks:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Complexity that leads to stasis</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Inability to scale</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Vendor dependence</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	As its complex in the very first go, it will not take off right away. It will take time for network industry and engineers to accept it and use it extensivly. But once SDN is implemented, its benefits are immense and cloud computing controlled by SDN will result in greater speed and efficiency. Not only cloud industry, but all the network industry will gain lots of benefits from it as it is just the start of the new era of network industry which is here to stay for a long time.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>References&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\n	<strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software-defined_networking" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software-defined_networking</a>&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\n	<a href="https://www.idc.com/getdoc.jsp?containerId=prUS25052314" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.idc.com/getdoc.jsp?containerId=prUS25052314&nbsp;</strong></a><br />\r\n	<a href="https://www.opennetworking.org/sdn-resources/sdn-definition" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.opennetworking.org/sdn-resources/sdn-definition</strong></a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '6d218-iowiki-software-defined-networking-sdn-image-1.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-15 09:55:36', 0),
(46, 'Effect of Temperature on Thermo Emf', 'In the complete study of this concept we will use some symbols. These are shown below:  Q­c – Temp of the cold junction  Qn – It is Neutral Temperature  Qi – In is the inversion temperature', 'Effect of Temperature on Thermo Emf, Seeback effect, variation of thermo-emf with temperature, Thermo-Emf variation with temperature', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Effect of Temperature on Thermo Emf', 'effect-of-temperature-on-thermo-emf', '<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The complete setup of apparatus is shown below to find the Effect of Temperature on Thermo Emf.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	In the complete study of this concept we will use some symbols. These are shown below:</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Q&shy;c &ndash; Temp of the cold junction</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Q<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">n</span>&nbsp;&ndash; It is Neutral Temperature</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Q<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>&nbsp;&ndash; In is the inversion temperature</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	A graph below shows the complete relation between the above three.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Some conclusions :</p>\r\n<ol style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Emf increases as the temperature of the hot junction increases. It goes on increasing until it reaches its maximum limit.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Neutral Temperature is the temperature at which the value of the emf becomes maximum.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		At a certain point when the value of emf reaches its maximum value, If we still goes on increasing the temperature then the emf value will goes on decreasing.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		The point or temperature at which the value of Thermo Emf becomes 0. That temperature is called temperature of Inversion. Its nature lies on temp of cold junction and thermo Couple.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		The graph between the Temperature and the thermo emf has a shape of Symmetrical Parabola. As we goes on increasing the Temperature then it will affect the thermo emf. The rise in temperature&nbsp; will change the direction of Thermo emf. The equation is shown below :</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp; ᶓ= &alpha;Ѳ+&beta;Ѳ<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="line-height: 23.8px;">ᶓ is called as Induced EMF</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&alpha; and &beta; are constants</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	I hope you will like article on Effect of Temperature on Thermo Emf. To stay updated please subscribe to the site feed.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '94204-effect-of-temperature-on-thermo-emf.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-16 08:50:10', 0),
(47, 'Difference between RIB(Routing information Base) and Routing Table', 'Difference between RIB(Routing information Base) and Routing Table', 'RIB, Routing Information Base, Routing Table, RIB vs Routing Table', 'Gagandeep Singh', 'Difference between RIB(Routing information Base) and Routing Table', 'difference-between-ribrouting-information-base-and-routing-table', '<h1>\r\n	Difference between RIB(Routing information Base) and Routing Table</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n	What if I told you that RIB(Routing Information Base) and Routing Table are not the same ?, around 90 percent of network engineers will say, that I have gone nuts, as many books claims that RIB is just another hot name of Routing Table. But this is not the reality.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/4bfc0-iowiki-rib-and-routing-table.jpg"><img alt="iowiki.com - Difference between RIB(Routing information Base) and Routing Table" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/4bfc0-iowiki-rib-and-routing-table.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 309px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>RIB(Routing Information Base</strong>) is actually a local view about information from a routing protocol. For example, every routing protocol(RIP,OSPF,EIGRP,BGP) has its RIB enteries.&nbsp; BGP generates BGP RIB Table that we can see with <strong>&ldquo;show ip bgp&rdquo;</strong> command. BGP Table is the result of routing information received and generated locally. There are situations where we have route entry in BGP Table, but when we check routing table by issuing command &ldquo;show ip route&rdquo;, then the route entry that was in BGP Table is not present in the routing table. It can be because of <strong>&ldquo;Unreachable Next-hop address&rdquo;</strong> or because of various other reasons.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	So in human&rsquo;s language, we can say that &ldquo;<strong>show ip bgp&rdquo;</strong> displays the RIB built by BGP, while &ldquo;show ip route&rdquo; displays the routing table, which is derived from the RIB Information, as the best and valid information is placed in the Routing Table from RIB.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><u>&nbsp;</u></strong></p>\r\n<h2>\r\n	To check RIB&nbsp; for each protocol, below are the commands -:</h2>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>RIP(Routing Information Protocol) &ndash; show ip rip database</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>R1#sh ip rip database</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1.0.0.0/8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; auto-summary</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1.1.1.1/32&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; directly connected, Loopback1</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.0.0.0/8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; auto-summary</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.2.2.2/32</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	[1] via 10.1.1.2, 00:00:22, FastEthernet0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3.0.0.0/8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; auto-summary</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3.3.3.3/32</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	[2] via 10.1.1.2, 00:00:06, FastEthernet0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	10.0.0.0/8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; auto-summary</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	10.1.1.0/30&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; directly connected, FastEthernet0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	10.1.1.4/30</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	[1] via 10.1.1.2, 00:00:22, FastEthernet0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>EIGRP(Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol) &ndash; show ip eigrp topology all-links</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>R1#sh ip eigrp topology all-links</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	IP-EIGRP Topology Table for AS(1)/ID(1.1.1.1)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Codes: P &ndash; Passive, A &ndash; Active, U &ndash; Update, Q &ndash; Query, R &ndash; Reply,</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	r &ndash; reply Status, s &ndash; sia Status</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	P 3.3.3.3/32, 1 successors, FD is 435200, serno 12</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	via 10.1.1.2 (435200/409600), FastEthernet0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	P 2.2.2.2/32, 1 successors, FD is 409600, serno 7</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	via 10.1.1.2 (409600/128256), FastEthernet0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	P 1.1.1.1/32, 1 successors, FD is 128256, serno 2</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	via Connected, Loopback1</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	P 10.1.1.0/30, 1 successors, FD is 281600, serno 1</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	via Connected, FastEthernet0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	P 10.1.1.4/30, 1 successors, FD is 307200, serno 5</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	via 10.1.1.2 (307200/281600), FastEthernet0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>OSPF(Open Shortest Path First) &ndash; show ip ospf databse</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>R1#sh ip ospf da</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong> OSPF Router with ID (1.1.1.1) (Process ID 1)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Router Link States (Area 0)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Link ID&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ADV Router&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Age&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Seq#&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Checksum Link count</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1.1.1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 1.1.1.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&times;80000002&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0x00965A&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.2.2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2.2.2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&times;80000002 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 0x00F6C5 &nbsp; &nbsp; 3</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Net Link States (Area 0)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Link ID&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ADV Router&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Age&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Seq#&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Checksum</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	10.1.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2.2.2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&times;80000001 0x001A01</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>You can also use command &ndash; show ip ospf rib detail</strong></p>\r\n