;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1136&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0/0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	IS-IS Level-2 Link State Database:</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	LSPID&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LSP Seq Num&nbsp; LSP Checksum&nbsp; LSP Holdtime&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ATT/P/OL</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	R1.00-00&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * 0&times;00000004&nbsp;&nbsp; 0x68BD&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1186&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0/0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	R2.00-00&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&times;00000005&nbsp;&nbsp; 0x82D9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1184&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0/0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	R2.02-00&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&times;00000001&nbsp;&nbsp; 0xAB7F&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 816&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0/0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	R3.00-00&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&times;00000005&nbsp;&nbsp; 0xAC69&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1180&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0/0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	R3.01-00&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&times;00000001&nbsp;&nbsp; 0xE045&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1136&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0/0/0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>BGP(Border Gateway Protocol) &ndash; show ip bgp </strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>R1#sh ip bgp</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	BGP table version is 10, local router ID is 1.1.1.1</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Status codes: s suppressed, d damped, h history, * valid, &gt; best, i &ndash; internal,</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	r RIB-failure, S Stale</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Origin codes: i &ndash; IGP, e &ndash; EGP, ? &ndash; incomplete</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Network&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Next Hop&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Metric LocPrf Weight Path</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	*&gt; 1.1.1.1/32&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0.0.0.0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 32768&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; i</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	*&gt;i2.2.2.2/32&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10.1.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 100&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; i</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	*&gt;i3.3.3.3/32&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;10.1.1.6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 100&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; i</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	* i10.1.1.0/30&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10.1.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 100&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; i</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	*&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0.0.0.0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 32768&nbsp; &nbsp; i</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	*&gt;i10.1.1.4/30&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10.1.1.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 100&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; i</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	There&rsquo;s another reason that makes RIB different from Routing Table, i.e. In OSPF, if the <strong>forwarding address or FA for LSA 5</strong> is not reachable, in that case, we can see those LSA entries there&nbsp; in the ospf database with the help of <strong>&ldquo;show ip ospf database&rdquo;</strong>, but we won&rsquo;t see those routes in Routing Table, when we run <strong>&ldquo;show ip route&rdquo;.</strong></p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-18 09:40:58', 0),
(48, 'Cisco Switching Methods', 'In early 1980s, when enterprises started to experience slower performance on their networks, they created Ethernet(transparent) bridges to limit collision domains.  Store and Forward – It is the earliest method of forwarding data packets at Layer 2. In ', 'Cisco Switching methods, Cut through switching, Fragment Free switching, Store and Forward Switching, Layer 2 vs Layer 3 Switch, Multilayer Switch, Route Caching, Topology Based Switching, Cisco Express Forwarding, FIB, Forwarding Information Base, Route ', 'Gagandeep Singh', 'Cisco Switching Methods', 'cisco-switching-methods', '<h1>\r\n	Cisco Switching Methods</h1>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In early 1980s, when enterprises started to experience slower performance on their networks, they created Ethernet(transparent) bridges to limit collision domains. In the 1990s, advancements were made in integrated circuit technologies, which allowed bridge vendors to move the layer 2 forwarding decisions from Complex Instruction Set Computing(CISC) and Reduced Instruction Set Computing(RISC) based processors to application specific integrated circuits(ASICs) and field-programmable gate arrays(FPGAs), which reduced the packet-handling time within the bridge to tens of microseconds. It also helped bridge to handle many more ports without a performance penality, and from then my friends, the term &ldquo;ETHERNET SWITCH&rdquo; became popular.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A Layer 2 device.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Per-port collision domain.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		One broadcast domain, when switch doesn&rsquo;t have destination mac-address in its Content Addressable Memory(CAM) table.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Switch learns mac-address dynamically when some device tries to access some other device in LAN. Source MAC address is stored in the CAM table, while trying to reach towards destination.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		By default, aging time of a mac-address sitting idle is 300 seconds or 5 minutes.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		When we try to access any destination device, with destination mac-address already listed in mac-address-table, then frame is unicasted from source to destination.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>\r\n	Switching Methods -</h2>\r\n<div>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n			<b>Store and Forward &ndash; </b>It is the earliest method of forwarding data packets at Layer 2. In this method, switch copies complete ethernet frame into the switch and computes a CRC for errors. If some CRC error is found, the ethernet frame is dropped, and if there is no CRC error, the switch forwards the ethernet frame to the destination device. This kind of switching can cause delay in switching, as it copies whole ethernet frame and does CRC.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n			<b>Cut-through Switching</b> &ndash; In cut-through method, the switch copies into its memory only the destination address(first six bytes of frame), before making the switching decision. A switch operating in cut-through switching mode reduces delay because the switch starts to forward the ethernet frame as soon as it reads the destination mac-address, and determines the outgoing switchport. Problem related with cut-through switching is that the switch may forward bad frames as there is no error-checking.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n			<b>Fragment-Free Switching</b> &ndash; It is an advanced version of cut-through. The switches operating in cut-through switching reads only upto the destination mac-address field in the ethernet frame before making a switching decision. The switches operating in fragment-free switching needs atleast 64 bytes of the frame, if there&rsquo;s any error in the first &nbsp;64 bytes of the frame, then the frame gets dropped. It needs atleast 64 bytes of frame to avoid forwarding ethernet runt frames(ethernet frames smaller than 64 bytes). That&rsquo;s why, it is also known as Runtless switching.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>L2 vs L3 Switches :-</b></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>&nbsp;</b></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>L2 Switches &ndash; </b>Does only switching ; Models &ndash; Cisco 2950, 2960, Nexus 3000</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>L3 Switches &ndash; </b>Switching&nbsp;+ Routing ; Models &ndash; Cisco 3550, 3560, 3750, 3800, 4500, 6500, 6800, Nexus 5000 Series, Nexus 7000 Series</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>&nbsp;</b></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>Multilayer Switch Operation &ndash; </b>Switches such as 3560, 3750, 4500, 6500, 6800 can also forward frames based on Layer 3 and Layer 4 information contained in packets. This is known as Multilayer Switching.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>&nbsp;</b></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>Types of Multilayer Switching :-&nbsp;</b></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b>&nbsp;</b></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n			<b>Route Caching &ndash; </b>It is also known as first generation of MLS, it requires a route processor(RP) and a switching engine(SE). RP must process traffic flow&rsquo;s first packet to determine the path, SE listens to the first packet and to the resulting decision for the next hop towards the destination, and sets up the shortcut cache in its MLS cache. Afterwards SE forwards same traffic flow based on enteries in the cache. It is also known as &ldquo;Netflow LAN Switching&rdquo;, &ldquo;Flow-Based Switching&rdquo;, &ldquo;Demand-based-switching&rdquo;, and &ldquo;route-once, switch many&rdquo;.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>\r\n			<b>Topology Based -&nbsp; </b>Second generation of MLS, utilizing specialized hardware. This is ultrafast. Layer 3 routing information builds and prepopulates a single database of the entire network topology. With an efficient table lookup in hardware, packets can be forwarded at high rates. The longest match found in the FIB database is used as the correct layer 3 destination. Routing Information Base(RIB) syncs with Forwarding Information Base(FIB). As the RIB changes, FIB also changes. This type of MLS is known as Cisco Express Forwarding(CEF).</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<img alt="iowiki-cisco-switching-gif" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/72814-flash-iowiki-switching.gif" style="width: 500px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '47bc4-iowiki-rabbit-and-tortoise-cisco-switching-methods.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-18 10:04:16', 0),
