(50, 'EIGRP Graceful Shutdown', ' With the help of this EIGRP Graceful Shutdown, EIGRP neighbor relationships works more efficiently as they synchronize and recalculate neighbor relationships without relying on hold-time expiration.     It warns a peer that it is about to go down, and th', 'EIGRP Graceful Shutdown, EIGRP, CCNP, CCDP, CCDA, CCIE', 'Gagandeep Singh', 'EIGRP Graceful Shutdown', 'eigrp-graceful-shutdown', '<h3>\r\n	<span style="font-size: medium;">Hello folks, Today I&rsquo;ll write about Graceful shutdown feature in EIGRP, which is a wonderful feature and also a part of CCIE Blueprint. So lets start, A graceful shutdown allows an EIGRP process, which is about to shut down to send a goodbye message to tell all adjacent peers that a topology change is about to occur.</span></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		With the help of this feature, EIGRP neighbor relationships works more efficiently as they synchronize and recalculate neighbor relationships without relying on hold-time expiration.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		It warns a peer that it is about to go down, and there&rsquo;s no need for hold-time expiration.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>What exactly is a Goodbye Messages that make Graceful Shutdown work ?</b></p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Starting with Cisco IOS 12.3(2), 12.3(3)B, 12.3(2)T and later, these messages are sent within Hello Packets, Goodbye message sends all K values set to 255 as shown in the figure below, while taking down all the peers on an interface.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<img alt="eigrp-graceful-wireshark-iowiki" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/80936-eigrp-graceful-wireshark-iowiki.png" style="width: 500px; height: 392px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<b>If some router does not support Goodbye message,&nbsp;it will display the message as K-Value mismatch and the following output -:</b></div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		&nbsp;</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		*Feb20 14:33:46.211: %DUAL-5-NBRCHANGE: IP-EIGRP(0) 1: Neighbor 192.168.1.1 (Ethernet0/0) is down: K-value mismatch</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<b>&nbsp;</b></div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<b>For supported software releases, following &nbsp;is the output when goodbye message is received -:&nbsp;</b></div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		*Feb20 14:33:46.433: %DUAL-5-NBRCHANGE: IP-EIGRP(0) 1: Neighbor 192.168.1.1 (Ethernet0/0) is down: Interface Goodbye received</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		One thing also need to be noted is that if any router that does not support &nbsp;Goodbye Messages does not disrupt the network operation, It will then use the hold down timer to determine a down peer.</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<b>An EIGRP router will send a goodbye message on an interface only if:</b></div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>\r\n				The EIGRP <strong>network </strong>command is removed.</li>\r\n			<li>\r\n				The EIGRP process is shut down (using <strong>no router eigrp</strong>).</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>But it will not send any goodbye messages if-:</b></p>\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>\r\n				An interface is shut down</li>\r\n			<li>\r\n				or the router is reloaded</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '64793-eigrp-graceful-shutdown-iowiki.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-18 10:36:33', 0),
(55, 'Verification of Faradays First law', 'Case 1 : In the beginning the cathode plate is properly cleaned, dried and weighed. Now we a fixed time constant amount of current is passed through the electrolyte. Now after completing the process of passing current again weigh your cathode rod and veri', 'Verification of faradays first law, Faradays law of verification, Faraday Laws', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Verification of Faradays First law', 'verification-of-faradays-first-law', '<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Case 1</span>&nbsp;: In the beginning the cathode plate is properly cleaned, dried and weighed. Now we a fixed time constant amount of current is passed through the electrolyte. Now after completing the process of passing current again weigh your cathode rod and verify the mass of the deposits.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Case 2</span>: Now increase the amount of current passed. Let&rsquo;s double the amount of current passed. You will observe that the mass deposit amount will also be doubled.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Case 3</span>: In this case double the time for which we are passing the current. Don&rsquo;t alter (change) the amount of current passed. The current should remain constant.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	From the above cases it is concluded that the mass deposit on the electrodes is directly proportional to the time and the charge passed through the circuit.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The apparatus figure is shown below:</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Faradays second law verification</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	To verify the faradays second law we have to connect all these three voltameters in series. The figure below shows the connection between the voltameters.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	After conducting this experiment we will find that the total mass deposit on the cathode will be directly proportional to their chemical equivalents if the same amount of charge is passed.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	M<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">Cu</span>&nbsp;: m<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">H2</span>&nbsp;:m<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">Ag</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	1 : 31.5 : 108</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-21 12:01:11', 0);
