(56, 'Leclanche Cell', 'It consists of a glass vessel in which ammonium chloride is taken as an electrolyte. A porous pot containing MnO 2 i.e. (Manganese Dioxide) and Charcoal powder is placed in a glass vessel. When carbon rod is placed in the porous pot and the zinc rod is pl', 'Leclanche Cell, Cells', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Leclanche Cell', 'leclanche-cell', '<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	It consists of a glass vessel in which ammonium chloride is taken as an electrolyte. A porous pot containing MnO</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">2</span>&nbsp;i.e. (Manganese Dioxide) and Charcoal powder is placed in a glass vessel. When carbon rod is placed in the porous pot and the zinc rod is placed in the glass vessel the following reactions take place.</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	2NH<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">4&nbsp;</span>Cl &mdash;-&gt; 2NH<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;3</span>&nbsp;+ 2Cl&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">-</span>&nbsp;+ 2H&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">+</span></div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Zn &mdash;&gt; Zn&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">++</span>&nbsp; + 2e&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">-</span></div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Zn&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">++</span>&nbsp; + 2 Cl&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">-</span>&nbsp; &mdash;&gt; Zncl<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;2</span></div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&nbsp;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&ndash;</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	2NH<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">4&nbsp;</span>Cl + Zn &mdash;&gt; 2NH<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;3</span>&nbsp;+ 2H&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">+</span>&nbsp;+&nbsp; 2e&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">-</span>&nbsp;+ Zncl<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;2</span></div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Due to excess electrons the Zn rod acts as a negatively charged electrode and ammonia will escape in the form of gas. The hydrogen ion diffuse into the porous pot and react with MnO&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">2</span>&nbsp;to form&nbsp; Mn<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">2</span>O<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;3</span>&nbsp;and water.</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By taking two electrons from the carbon rod the electron deficiency of electrons on carbon rod take place. So, due to this carbon rod act as a positively charged electrode.</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2H&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">+</span>&nbsp; + MnO&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">2</span>&nbsp;+ 2e&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">-</span></div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &mdash;-&gt; Mn<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;2</span>O<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;3</span>&nbsp;+ H<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;2</span>O</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	The emf of Leclanche cell is 1.45V.</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Note</span></span>:-</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Charcoal is used to increase the conductivity of MnO<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;2</span>.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Leclanche cell cannot be used in a circuit to take a steady current because MnO<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">&nbsp;2</span>&nbsp;is a slow depolarizer.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'e353b-leclanche-cell.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-27 09:49:51', 0),
(57, 'Mendeleevs Periodic Table', 'Classification of elements was first done by Russian Chemist Dmitri Ivanovich  Mendeleev (professor at university in Moscow). He said that when the elements are arranged in order of their increasing atomic weights then, the elements with similar propertie', '', '', 'Mendeleevs Periodic Table', 'mendeleevs-periodic-table', '<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">Classification of elements was first done by Russian Chemist Dmitri Ivanovich&nbsp; Mendeleev (professor at university in Moscow). He said that when the elements are arranged in order of their increasing atomic weights then, the elements with similar properties are repeated after regular intervals. While classifying the elements Mendeleev leaves some blank spaces as he predicts that there will be some elements which were not known yet. In-fact he also predicted the properties of the unknown elements by analysing the properties of other elements .For example, Mendeleev predicted the properties of gallium and germanium which were not known at that time. He named these elements as eka-aluminium and eka-silicon because he believed that these elements would have properties similar to the properties of aluminium and silicon.</span></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>Characteristics&nbsp;of Mendeleevs Periodic Table</strong></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Mendeleev&rsquo;s periodic table was published in 1872. When noble gases or inert gases were discovered then a new group was added to the Mendeleev&rsquo;s periodic table and was called the Zero group. Modified Mendeleev&rsquo;s periodic table consists of nine vertical columns called groups and six horizontal rows called periods. The elements on the left side of each group constitute sub-group A while those placed on right side form sub-group B. Group VIII contains nine elements in three sets each containing three elements. Group Zero consists of only vertical column of noble or inert gases.</p>\r\n<h3 data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Significance of Mendeleevs Periodic Table</b></h3>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Mendeleev&rsquo;s periodic table makes the study of elements easier and in a systematic way. Thus knowing the properties of one element in a group or period we can predict the properties of other element also.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Only 63 elements were known at that time when Mendeleev&rsquo;s periodic table was formulated. Mendeleev left some blank spaces in his periodic table which represent the unknown elements. Later on Mendeleev predicted the properties of the unknown elements, as he predicted the properties of gallium and germanium. After some time when these elements were invented, it was found that the properties of these elements were similar to those predicted by Mendeleev.</p>\r\n<h4 data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Defects in Mendeleevs Periodic Table</b></h4>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Hydrogen is placed in group&nbsp;<span data-mce-style="font-size: medium;" style="font-size: medium;">1</span>A in&nbsp;Mendeleev&#39;s Periodic Table<b>&nbsp;</b>&nbsp;but it resembles the elements of both the group 1A and group VIIA. So the position of Hydrogen is not fixed in Mendeleev&rsquo;s periodic table.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	According to Mendeleev, isotopes should be placed at different places in a periodic table. So isotopes of hydrogen i.e., Protium, deuterium and tritium should also be placed at different places. But there is no position of an isotope of an element in his periodic table.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Nine elements of group VIII are arranged in three different triads without any reason because they have not been assigned any proper space in the periodic table.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	In Mendeleev&rsquo;s periodic table similar elements are placed in different groups while some dissimilar elements are grouped together.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	These were the main Defects of Mendeleevs Periodic Table.</p>\r\n', 'f1b06-mendeleevs-periodic-table.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-28 01:32:28', 0),
(58, 'Testing ios app on device without developer account', 'Apple has made a recent announcement in the Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) of 2015 that apps can be tested in devices even if you don’t have a paid Developer Account and it’s possible in Xcode 7 and above versions.', 'test ios app on device without developer account, debugging ios app on device without developer account, testing xcode project on device without developer account, debugging xcode project on device without developer account, run xcode project on device wi', 'Amanpreet Singh', 'Testing ios app on device without developer account', 'testing-ios-app-on-device-without-developer-account', '<p>\r\n	Apple has made a recent announcement in the Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) of 2015 that apps can be tested in devices even if you don&#39;t have a paid Developer Account and it&#39;s possible in Xcode 7 and above versions.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	So, just follow the below steps if you want to debug your Xcode projects in your own device without purchasing an Apple Developer Account. Note that you must have an existing Apple id and if you don&#39;t, you can create a new one through this link:-&nbsp;<a href="https://appleid.apple.com/in/#!&amp;page=create">Get an Apple ID</a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Step 1</strong>:- Open <strong>Xcode</strong> -&gt; <strong>Preferences</strong> -&gt; <strong>Accounts</strong> -&gt; Click on the <strong>+</strong> sign -&gt; <strong>Select Add Apple ID&hellip; </strong>and then you will be prompted to Enter your <strong>Apple ID</strong> and <strong>Password</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a>After</a>&nbsp;you have successfully signed in, your Apple ID will appear in Accounts as shown below:-</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/73b7f-testing-ios-app-on-device-without-developer-account.jpg"><img alt="testing-ios-app-on-device-without-developer-account" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/73b7f-testing-ios-app-on-device-without-developer-account.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 352px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Step 2</strong>:- Then Go to <strong>Project Navigator</strong> -&gt; Select your <strong>Project</strong> name -&gt; <strong>TARGETS</strong> -&gt; <strong>General</strong> -&gt; <strong>Identity</strong> -&gt; <strong>Team</strong> (Select your name from the Team dropdown)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Step 3</strong>:- Then connect your device to Mac and select the device (In place of Simulator) from <strong>Schema</strong> menu.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Step 4</strong>:- Then under the Team dropdown select Fix Issue and you will see the warning disappears.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Step 5</strong>:- Finally, click on the Run button and as soon as Xcode finishes the installation of your app you will see the app running on your device.</p>\r\n<div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<div id="_com_1" uage="JavaScript">\r\n			<p>\r\n				&nbsp;</p>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'e090d-testing-ios-app-on-device-without-developer-account-1.png', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-02-28 08:22:05', 0),
(59, 'Different Kinds of Boilers', 'The purpose of the boiler, as pointed out earlier, is to generate steam at the predetermined pressure and temperature by using heat produced by the combustion of fuel. The evaporation (steam raising) capacity of the boiler depends upon:', 'Equivalent Evaporation of water,  Grate area, Boiler Efficiency, calculate boiler frequency', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Different Kinds of Boilers', 'different-kinds-of-boilers', '<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Apparatus:</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Cochran Boiler; Babcock and Wilcox Boiler; Benson Boiler.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Theory</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	The purpose of the boiler, as pointed out earlier, is to generate steam at the predetermined pressure and temperature by using heat produced by the combustion of fuel. The evaporation (steam raising) capacity of the boiler depends upon:</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	(a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Grate area i.e the amount of fuel the boiler can consume</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	(b)&nbsp;&nbsp; Heating surface i.e. the quantity of heat which the boiler can absorb,</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	The evaporation capacity may be expressed as kg/hr-m<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;of heating surface or kg/kg of fuel burnt.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	If these parameters are kept constant, the amount of water which a boiler can evaporate further depends upon:</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	(a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Condition of pressure and temperature under which the boiler is operating,</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	(b)&nbsp;&nbsp; Quality of steam being raised (wet, dry or superheated).</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	(c)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Temperature of feed water being supplied to the boiler.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Thus it may be realized that number of kg of water evaporated per hour is not an exact measure of the performance of the boiler. For making a comparison of the relative evaporation capacity of the boiler, the water is supposed to evaporate under the following standard conditions.</p>\r\n<ol style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Feed water is supplied to the boiler at 100&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">o</span>C.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Evaporation of steam takes place at the same temperature of 100<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">&nbsp;o</span>C</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		The steam raised is just dry and saturated.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	When water evaporates under these conditions, it requires 538.9 kcal of heat which equals the latent heat of steam at 100&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">o</span>C under atmospheric pressure of 1.0332 kgf/cm<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Equivalent Evaporation of water</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&ldquo;Evaporation which would be obtained if the feed water were supplied at 100&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">o</span>C and converted into dry saturated steam at 100&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">o</span>C at the standard atmospheric pressure of 1.0332kgf/cm<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="line-height: 23.8px;">Let&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wa = weight of water actually evaporated into steam per&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; kg of coal burnt at the working pressure.</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Hs = specific enthalpy of steam at the working pressure.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	hw = specific enthalpy (sensible heat) of feed water.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Then heat absorbed by the water at actual working pressure = Wa (Hs-hw)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (i)</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Further if Wo is equivalent evaporation, then</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Heat absorbed at the water under standard conditions</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	= We x Lo&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (ii)</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	where&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lo = enthalpy of evaporation (latent heat) of steam at</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	1 kgf/cm<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;and 100&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">o</span>C</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	= 539 kcal/kg (2256 kj/kg)</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Equating (i) and (ii), we get</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	We =&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Wa(Hs-hw)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>kg/kg of coal burnt</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Lo &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (iii)</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	=<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Wa(Hs-hw)</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	539 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; when Hs and hw are expressed in Kcal</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	=<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Wa(Hs-hw)</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	2256 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; when Hs and hw are expressed in KJ</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	In equation (iii), the factor (Hs-hw/Lo) is always greater than unity and is known as factor of evaporation or generation factor. The factor of evaporation may be defined as the ratio of heat absorbed by 1kg of feed water under working conditions to that absorbed by 1kg of water from and at 100&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">o</span>C.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Boiler Efficiency</span></span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">&nbsp;</span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; It is defined as the ratio of heat energy utilized by feed water in converting it into steam in the boiler to the heat energy realized by complete combustion of fuel during the same time.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Boiler Efficiency = E<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">nergy absorbed by feed water</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Energy absorbed by fuel</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	h&nbsp; =&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Wa(Hs-hw)</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Wf&nbsp; x Calorific value of fuel</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Where&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wa = actual evaporation of steam/hr</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Hs&nbsp; = total heat of steam produced ,</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Hw = sensible heat of feed water,</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Wf = weight of fuel consumed/ hr.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	However, if the boiler is equipped with an economizer and a super heater, then efficiency of the unit is called overall efficiency of the boiler plant and it takes into account the efficiency of all the three elements namely: boiler, economizer and super heater.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">&nbsp;Observation and Calculations</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">&nbsp;</span>Heat absorbed by the water at actual working pressure&nbsp; = Wa(Hs-hw)</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Heat absorbed bt the water under standard conditions &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;=&nbsp; We x Lo</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Equivalent evaporation, We =&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Wa(Hs-hw)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>kg/kg of coal burnt</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Lo</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	=<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Wa(Hs-hw)</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	539&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (when Hs and hw are expressed in Kcal)</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	=<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Wa(Hs-hw)</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	2256 &nbsp;&nbsp; (when Hs and hw are expressed in KJ)</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Wa = weight of water actually evaporated into steam per kg of coal&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; burnt at the working pressure.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Hs = specific enthalpy of steam at the working pressure.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	hw = specific enthalpy (sensible heat) of feed water.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Lo = enthalpy of evaporation (latent heat) of steam at</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	1 kgf/cm<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;and 100&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">o</span>C</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	= 539 kcal/kg (2256 kj/kg)</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Boiler Efficiency,<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">h</span>&nbsp;&nbsp; =&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration: underline;">Wa (Hs-hw)</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Wf&nbsp; x Calorific value of fuel</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span>Wa = actual evaporation of steam/hr</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Hs&nbsp; = total heat of steam produced ,</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Hw = sensible heat of feed water,</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Wf = weight of fuel consumed/ hr.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; f