ask: 255.128.0.0 or /9 and usable IP addresses will be : 8388606&quot;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n    elif y &gt; 8388608 and y &lt; 16777217: print &quot;Subnet Mask: 255.0.0.0 or /8 and usable IP addresses will be : 16777214&quot;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n    else :print &quot;You are at wrong Planet....:p....:-p&quot;</div>\r\n<p>\r\n    &nbsp;</p>\r\n</code></pre>\r\n    <strong>Output of the script is given below :</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n    &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n    <img alt="python-script-to-find-best-subnet-mask-according-to-requirement" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/ab6c5-python-script-to-find-best-subnet-mask-according-to-requirements-using-if-anf-elif-statements-iowiki.png" style="width: 499px; height: 156px; margin: 20px;" /></p>\r\n', '723ae-python-logo.png', 'Published', 0, 8, '2016-03-07 12:51:20', 0),
(63, 'Static Routing', 'In simple english or when we put the definition in simpler terms, static routing means to enter the paths towards destination manually or statically. ', 'Static Routing in Ipv4, CCNA, Routing, Cisco Static Routing configuration', 'Gagandeep Singh', 'Ipv4 Static Routing', 'ipv4-static-routing', '<p>\r\n	Routing is to find the best path to reach destination. Routing can be done in two ways :</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Static Routing</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Dynamic Routing</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>\r\n	In this document, major focus is towards Static Routing.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		What is Static Routing ?</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		In simple english or when we put the definition in simpler terms, static routing means to enter the paths towards destination manually or statically. In static routing, total control can be achieved as all the paths are determined by Network Engineer or Network Administrator by itself. We tell the router that in order to reach the destination, which path he can use.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Where to use Static Routing ?</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		May be in smaller networks, where we do not need to issue large number of static route commands. Also where we need total control which cannot be provided by there counterparts like Dynamic Routing Protocols.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		How can i configure static routing on my Windows Machine ?</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Well its easy, you just need to login via Administrator and start the Command Prompt, and then you can use the following command :</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul style="list-style-type:circle;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		route add [destination-network]&nbsp; mask [destination-mask] [gateway]</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		example - route add 10.1.1.0 mask 255.255.255.252&nbsp; 192.168.1.1</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Screenshot displaying the Static route configuration windows 7 is shown below :<br />\r\n	<img alt="add-static-routes-in-windows-machine" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/d9815-add-static-routes-in-windows-machine.png" style="width: 496px; height: 34px; margin: 20px;" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In order to view routing table in windows, you can use &quot;route print&quot; command in command prompt. Screenshot showing output of route print is given below :</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="route-print-command-in-windows-machine-iowiki" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/30520-route-print.png" style="width: 500px; height: 510px; margin: 20px;" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	To delete routes on Windows machine, we can use &quot;route delete [destination-network] mask [destination-mask] [gateway]&quot;.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	To delete the routes we added previously, we can use the following command :</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&quot;route delete 10.1.1.0 mask 255.255.255.252 192.168.1.1&quot;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Screenshot displaying the static route deletion is given below :</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="delete-static-routes-with-route-delete-command-in-windows-command-prompt-iowiki" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/b6f3f-route-del.png" style="width: 497px; height: 31px; margin: 20px;" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		How can i configure Static Routing on&nbsp; Cisco Routers ?</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Syntax is given below :</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp; ip route&nbsp; [destination-network] [destination-mask] [gateway]</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	We will use the topology below for example :</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="Static-Routing-topology-iowiki" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/7a18f-static-routing-topology-iowiki.png" style="width: 501px; height: 217px; margin: 20px;" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In the above topology R1 has one LAN connected with IP Network 10.1.1.0/29 and R3 has other LAN connected with IP Network 10.1.1.8/29, In order to reach 10.1.1.8 from R1, we have two paths :</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Path A - R1 - R2 - R4 - 10.1.1.8/29</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Path B - R1 - R3 - R4 - 10.1.1.8/29</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Lets start configuring all the routers :</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>R1 Configuration </strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<textarea cols="50" rows="4">ip route 10.1.1.20 255.255.255.252 10.1.1.18\r\nip route 10.1.1.28 255.255.255.252 10.1.1.26\r\nip route 10.1.1.8 255.255.255.248 10.1.1.18\r\nip route 10.1.1.8 255.255.255.248 10.1.1.26\r\n</textarea></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>R2 Configuration</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<textarea cols="50" rows="2">ip route 10.1.1.0 255.255.255.248 10.1.1.17\r\nip route 10.1.1.8 255.255.255.248 10.1.1.22\r\n</textarea></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>R3 Configuration</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<textarea cols="50" rows="2">ip route 10.1.1.0 255.255.255.248 10.1.1.25\r\nip route 10.1.1.8 255.255.255.248 10.1.1.30\r\n</textarea></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>R4 Configuration</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<textarea cols="50" rows="4">ip route 10.1.1.0 255.255.255.248 10.1.1.29\r\nip route 10.1.1.0 255.255.255.248 10.1.1.21\r\nip route 10.1.1.24 255.255.255.252 10.1.1.29\r\nip route 10.1.1.16 255.255.255.252 10.1.1.21\r\n</textarea></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>We can check the routing table on any router by using &quot;show ip route&quot; command. Following is the output of &quot;show ip route&quot; on R1 :</strong><br />\r\n	<img alt="show-ip-route-command-output-iowiki" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/f205a-show-ip-route-iowiki.png" style="width: 501px; height: 276px; margin: 20px;" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>As you can check from above output, &quot;show ip route&quot; can be used to view the full routing table, while in case if we want to check only routes that have been learnt only via Static Routing, then we can use &quot;show ip route static&quot; command. Routing table shows that in order to reach LAN 2 network from R1, we have two best paths in the routing table, one via 10.1.1.26 and other one via 10.1.1.18.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Let&#39;s check now, if we can ping from LAN 1 towards LAN 2, we will initiate a ping request from PC4 having IP address 10.1.1.2 in LAN 1 towards PC1 having IP address 10.1.1.10 in LAN 2. So let&#39;s do it :</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="static-routing-image-3-iowiki" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/a4a67-static-routing-image-3-iowiki.png" style="width: 499px; height: 263px; margin: 20px;" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Floating Static Routing - Primary / Backup Scenario, that&#39;s it. :-p</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In order to make one path as primary and other one as secondary, you need to tune the administrative distance, which is &quot;1&quot; be default for static routing.&nbsp; As on R1, we have two paths towards 10.1.1.8/29, one via 10.1.1.18 and other one via 10.1.1.26, and as both of them has Administrative distance value of 1.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Suppose we have 10.1.1.18 link with bandwidth of 20Mbps and 10.1.1.26 with the bandwidth capacity of 2Mbps, and we want link towards 10.1.1.8 via 10.1.1.18 to be our best path, so we will change the administrative distance of static route 10.1.1.8 via 10.1.1.26 to be larger than &quot;1&quot;, as static route 10.1.1.8 via 10.1.1.18 has lower administrative distance value, therefore automatically it becomes the best path. In the following configuration, i have changed the AD value via 10.1.1.26 to &quot;7&quot; from &quot;1&quot; to make the route towards 10.1.1.8 via 10.1.1.26 to be less preferable.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Configuration to change Administrative distance is given below :</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>ip route&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; destination-network&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; destination-mask &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;next-hop-id&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; administrative-distance </strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>When put in our terms, the config will be :</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>ip route 10.1.1.8&nbsp; 255.255.255.248&nbsp; 10.1.1.26&nbsp; 7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-08 08:58:25', 0),
(64, 'Instruction Format of 8085 Microprocessor', 'One Byte Instructions: This instruction uses a single Byte. That single byte specifies both opcode i.e. (Operation Code) and Operand. It consists of opcode and operand.', '8085 microprocessor instruction format, 8085 instruction format, 8085 instruction set, Microprocessor instruction format,  8085 microprocessor, Intel 8085 microprocessor', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Instruction Format of 8085 Microprocessor', 'instruction-format-of-8085-microprocessor', '<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	An instruction is a command given to the computer to perform some specific task. Each instruction is basically divided into two parts.</p>\r\n<ol style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Opcode &ndash; It specifies the basic operation to be performed.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Operand: Operands are those entities on which operation is to be performed.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Let&rsquo;s take an example to clear the difference between the operator and the operand. E.g A ADD B</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	A and B are operands and ADD is the opcode.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	In 8085 microprocessor instructions are classified on the basis of word length and these are given below in detail.</p>\r\n<ol style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		One byte Instructions Or One Word Instructions</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Two byte Instructions Or Two Word Instructions</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Three byte Instructions Or Three Word Instructions</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">One Byte Instructions:</span>&nbsp;This instruction uses a single Byte. That single byte specifies both opcode i.e. (Operation Code) and Operand. It consists of opcode and operand.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Eg.</p>\r\n<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="box-sizing: border-box; border-spacing: 0px; border-collapse: collapse; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<tbody style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Instruction</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Opcode</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Operand</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Binary Code</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Hexadecimal Code</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				MOV D,A</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				MOV</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				D, A</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				01 010 011</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				57H(one Byte)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	In the binary code above the first two bits (01) are for the MOV instruction.</p>\r\n<ul style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Next three bits 010 are for register D.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Last three bits 011 are for the register A. Register A means Accumulator register.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The above instruction is an 8 bit instruction. That&rsquo;s why it is called as One Byte Instruction.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Example 2</p>\r\n<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="box-sizing: border-box; border-spacing: 0px; border-collapse: collapse; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<tbody style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Instruction</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Opcode</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Operand</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Binary Code</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Hexadecimal Code</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				ADD C</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				ADD</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				C</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				1000 0001</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				81H(One Byte)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The above instruction will add the contents of the register C to the contents of the accumulator register.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The 8 bit binary code for ADD instruction is 1000 and for register C is 0001. The operands and opcodes are contained in single byte that why it is called as single byte instruction. One operand is register C and the other operand is automatically assumed to be the accumulator register.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Example 3</p>\r\n<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="box-sizing: border-box; border-spacing: 0px; border-collapse: collapse; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<tbody style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Instruction</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Opcode</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Operand</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Binary Code</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Hexadecimal Code</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				RAL</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				RAL</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				&nbsp; &mdash;&mdash;&mdash;-</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				0001 0111</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				17H(One byte)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The function of the RAL instruction is to move the contents of the accumulator register to the left by one bit. In this instruction operand is not specified. The operand is assumed to be the accumulator register. This instruction only copies the 8 binary bits(0001 0111). So, it is also a single byte instruction.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Two byte Instructions:</span>&nbsp;In this first byte specifies the operation code and the second byte specifies operand data.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	e.g.</p>\r\n<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="box-sizing: border-box; border-spacing: 0px; border-collapse: collapse; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<tbody style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Instruction</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Opcode</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Operand</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Binary Code</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Hexadecimal Code</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				MVI A</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Data MVI</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				A, Data(8-bit)</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				0011 1110</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				3EH(First Byte) Data(8 bit) Second Byte</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The function of MVI A is to move the 8 bit data into the accumulator register. Here, one byte is required for Opcode and second byte us required for data.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Three Byte Instruction:</span>&nbsp;In the three byte instruction first byte specifies the opcode , second and third byte specify the (16 bit ) memory address.</p>\r\n<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="box-sizing: border-box; border-spacing: 0px; border-collapse: collapse; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<tbody style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Instruction</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Opcode</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Operand</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Binary Code</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Hexadecimal Code</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				LDA 2800 H</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				LDA</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				2800 H</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				0011 00100000 00000010 0101</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				3A H (First Byte)00 H (Second Byte)28 H (Third Byte)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	First byte is required for opcode 3AH</p>\r\n<ul style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Second byte is required for 00H LSBS of the memory Location 2800H</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Third byte is required for 28 H MSB of the memory location 2800 H.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Example 2</p>\r\n<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="box-sizing: border-box; border-spacing: 0px; border-collapse: collapse; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<tbody style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Instruction</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Opcode</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Operand</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Binary Code</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				Hexadecimal Code</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				JMP 2050 H</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				JMP</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				2050 H</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				1100 00110101 00000010 0000</td>\r\n			<td style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px;" valign="top" width="128">\r\n				C3 (First Byte )50 (Second Byte )20(Third Byte)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The function of the above instruction is to transfer the program control to the memory location 2050 H.</p>\r\n<ul style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		The first byte specifies the opcode</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Second byte is the low order address (50 H) of the 16 bit &nbsp;memory address 2050 H.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		Third byte&nbsp; is the high order address (20 H) of the&nbsp; 16 bit memory address (2050 H).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '2a471-intel-8085-microprocessor.jpg', 'Published', 0, 3, '2016-03-08 09:55:28', 0),
(65, 'Shell script to check CPU/Disk/Memory Utilization, uptime, Last users, current connections ', 'Shell script to check CPU/Disk/Memory Utilization, uptime, Last login users, current connections and most expensive processes', 'Shell scripting, last login users shell script, cpu utilization shell script, memory utilization shell script, disk utilization shell script, last login users shell script, current connections shell script, most expensive process shell script', 'Gagandeep Singh', 'Shell script to check CPU/Disk/Memory Utilization, uptime, Last login users, current connections and most expensive processes', 'shell-script-to-check-cpudiskmemory-utilization-uptime-last-login-users-current-connections-and-most-expensive-processes', '<pre><code class="bash">\r\nuptime=$( uptime=${uptime%%.*}\r\nseconds=$((uptime%60))\r\nminutes=$((uptime/60%60))\r\nhours=$((uptime/60/60%24))\r\ndays=$((uptime/60/60/24))\r\necho "                 "\r\necho "Uptime: "\r\necho "                 "\r\necho "$days days, $hours hours, $minutes minutes, $seconds seconds"\r\necho "                 "\r\necho "-----------------------------------"\r\necho "                 "\r\necho "CPU/DISK/MEMORY Utilization"\r\necho "                 "\r\ndf -h | uptime | grep load | awk ''{printf "CPU LOAD: %.2f\\n",$(NF-2)}''\r\nfree -m | awk ''NR==2{printf "MEMORY TAKEN: %s/%sMB(%.2f%%)\\n",$3,$2,$3*100/$2}''\r\ndf -h | awk ''$NF=="/"{printf "Disk Usage: %d/%dGB(%s)\\n",$3,$3,$5}''\r\n\r\necho "                 "\r\necho "-----------------------------------"\r\necho "                 "\r\necho "Last 5 login users"\r\necho "                  "\r\nlast -n 5 | awk ''{print $1 " "$2 " "$4" "$5 " "$6 " "$7 " "$8 " "$9 " "$10 " "$11 }''\r\necho "                  "\r\necho "-----------------------------------"\r\necho "                  "\r\necho "CURRENT CONNECTIONS"\r\necho "                  "\r\nnetstat -n -A inet | awk ''{print $1 " "$4 " "$5 " "$6 }''\r\necho "                 "\r\necho "-----------------------------------"\r\necho "                 "\r\necho "Most Expensive Process"\r\necho "                  "\r\nps -eo pcpu,pid,user,args | sort -k1 -r | head -5 | awk ''{print $1 " "$2 " "$3 " "$4 " "$5 }''\r\n</code></pre>\r\n', '5fe4b-shell-script-funny.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-08 11:51:33', 0),
(66, 'Mid Point Ellipse Algorithm', '', 'Mid point algorithm in computer graphics,Mid Point Ellipse Algorithm', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Mid Point Ellipse Algorithm', 'mid-point-ellipse-algorithm', '<pre>\r\n<code class="cpp">\r\n//Program to perform Mid Point Ellipse Algorithm\r\n\r\n#include<iostream.h>\r\n#include<graphics.h>\r\n#include<stdio.h>\r\n#include<conio.h>\r\n#include<math.h>\r\n#define round(a)((int)(a+.5))\r\nvoid ellipseplotpoints(int xc, int yc, int x, int y);\r\nvoid ellipsemidpoint(int xc, int yc, int rx, int ry)\r\n{\r\nint rx2, ry2, tworx2, twory2, p,x=0,y,px,py;\r\nrx2=pow(rx,2);\r\nry2=pow(ry,2);\r\ntworx2=2*rx2;\r\ntwory2=2*ry2;\r\ny=ry;px=0;\r\npy=tworx2*y;\r\nellipseplotpoints(xc,yc,x,y);\r\n/*Region 1 */\r\np=round(ry2-(rx2*ry)+(.25*rx2));\r\nwhile(px<py) 2="" else="" p="p+ry2+px;" px="px+twory2;" py="py-tworx2;" region="" y="">0)\r\n{\r\ny--;\r\npy=py-tworx2;\r\nif(p&gt;0)\r\np=p+rx2-py;\r\nelse\r\n{\r\nx++;\r\npx=px+twory2;\r\np=p+rx2-py+px;\r\n}\r\nellipseplotpoints(xc,yc,x,y);\r\n}\r\n}\r\nvoid ellipseplotpoints(int xc, int yc, int x, int y)\r\n{\r\nputpixel(xc+x,yc+y,RED);\r\nputpixel(xc-x,yc+y,RED);\r\nputpixel(xc+x,yc-y,RED);\r\nputpixel(xc-x,yc-y,RED);\r\n}\r\nvoid main()\r\n{\r\nint xc,yc,rx,ry,gd=DETECT,gm;\r\ncout&lt;&lt;&quot;Enter center coordinates for ellipse:&quot;;\r\ncin&gt;&gt;xc&gt;&gt;yc;\r\ncout&lt;<endl<<"enter along="" cin="" enter="" radius="" y=""></endl<<"enter></py)></math.h></conio.h></stdio.h></graphics.h></iostream.h></code></pre>\r\n', '43046-mid-point-ellipse-algorithm.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-09 09:40:51', 0),
(67, 'Working of Wheat Stone Bridge', 'Step 1: Place the solenoid in ice at 0oC and make P = Q and adjust the value of R. So that the current through the galvanometer becomes 0.', 'Construction and working of wheat stone bridge, wheatstone bridge physics, Wheatstone Bridge Circuit , Principle of Wheatstone Bridge, Wheatstone Bridge Circuit Equations, Wheatstone Bridge Circuit Operation Basics , Introduction to Wheatstone Bridges,  W', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Working of Wheat Stone Bridge', 'working-of-wheat-stone-bridge', '<div dir="ltr" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	The steps of working of Wheat Stone Bridge are :</div>\r\n<div dir="ltr" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<b>Step 1</b>: Place the solenoid in ice at 0<sup>o</sup>C and make P = Q and adjust the value of R. So that the current through the galvanometer becomes 0. Let it takes place when<br />\r\n	X = R<sub>o</sub><br />\r\n	P/Q = R/R<sub>o</sub>&nbsp;[bcoz P/Q=R/X]<br />\r\n	R<sub>o</sub>&nbsp;= QR/P &hellip;&hellip;(1)</div>\r\n<div dir="ltr" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>Step 2</b>: Place the solenoid in boiling water at 100<sup>o</sup>C. Adjust the value of R so that current through the galvanometer becomes zero. In this situation<br />\r\n		R =&gt; R<sup>1</sup><br />\r\n		X =&gt; R<sub>100</sub><br />\r\n		So, P/Q = R<sup>1</sup>/R<sub>100</sub><br />\r\n		R<sub>100</sub>&nbsp;= QR<sup>1</sup>/P<br />\r\n		<br />\r\n		<br />\r\n		<b>Step 3</b>: Place the solenoid into a bath at temp &lsquo;t&rsquo;and adjust the value of R so that the current through the galvanometer becomes 0. In this situation<br />\r\n		R = R<sup>&rsquo;&rsquo;</sup>&nbsp;; X = R&nbsp;<sub>t</sub><br />\r\n		P/Q = R<sup>&rsquo;&rsquo;</sup>/R<sub>t</sub><br />\r\n		R<sub>t</sub>&nbsp;= QR&nbsp;<sub>&rsquo;&rsquo;</sub>/P<br />\r\n		<br />\r\n		<br />\r\n		<b>Step 4</b>: If &alpha; is the temp. coefficient of resistance of platinum wires then<br />\r\n		R<sub>100</sub>&nbsp;= R<sub>0</sub>[1 + &alpha; * 100]<br />\r\n		&alpha; = (R<sub>100</sub>&nbsp;- R<sub>0</sub>)/ (R<sub>0</sub>*100) &hellip;&hellip;.(2)<br />\r\n		Similarly at temp. &lsquo;t&rsquo;<br />\r\n		R<sub>t</sub>&nbsp;= R<sub>0</sub>[1 + &alpha;t]<br />\r\n		&alpha; = (R<sub>t</sub>&nbsp;- R<sub>0</sub>)/ (R<sub>0</sub>*t) &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;(3)<br />\r\n		From (2) and (3)<br />\r\n		(R<sub>100</sub>&nbsp;- R<sub>0</sub>)/ (R<sub>0</sub>*100) = (R<sub>t</sub>&nbsp;- R<sub>0</sub>)/ (R<sub>0</sub>&nbsp;* t)<br />\r\n		t = [(R<sub>t</sub>&nbsp;- R<sub>0</sub>)/(R<sub>100</sub>&nbsp;- R<sub>0</sub>)] * 100<br />\r\n		Putting the values<br />\r\n		t = (Q/P[R<sup>&rsquo;&rsquo;</sup>&nbsp;- R]) / (Q/P[R<sup>&rsquo;</sup>&nbsp;- R]) * 100<br />\r\n		t = (R<sup>&rsquo;&rsquo;</sup>&nbsp;- R)/ (R<sup>&rsquo;</sup>&nbsp;- R) * 100</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Hence we can say that by knowing R<sup>&rsquo;&rsquo;</sup>&nbsp;; R ; and R<sup>&rsquo;</sup>&nbsp;we can calculate the temperature of hot bath.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div dir="ltr" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n', '69e62-working-of-wheatstone-bridge.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-09 10:04:10', 0);
