(68, 'Architecture of Microprocessor 8085', 'The total available addressable memory size is 64 KB. Absolute addressing is used to jump within the available memory i.e. 64k. We have the freedom to locate our programs anywhere within this permissible range. ', 'Interrupts in Microprocessor 8085, Registers used in 8085 Microprocessor, Instruction Set used in Microprocessor 8085, Addressing modes of Microprocessor 8085, Architecture Diagram of 8085 Microprocessor, Internal Architecture of 8085 Microprocessor, 8085', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Architecture of Microprocessor 8085', 'architecture-of-microprocessor-8085', '<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">Let&rsquo;s first have a look on memory Architecture of Microprocessor 8085 first. The same memory space is occupied by all Programs, data as well as stack memories. The total available addressable memory size is 64 KB. Absolute addressing is used to jump within the available memory i.e. 64k. We have the freedom to locate our programs anywhere within this permissible range. Different instructions like jump, branch, call etc are used. These instructions are 16 bit instructions. They are used to jump anywhere in the memory space specified above.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n<a href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/bcddc-architecture-of-microprocessor-8085.jpg" class="fancybox">\r\n<img alt="architecture-of-microprocessor-8085" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/bcddc-architecture-of-microprocessor-8085.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 330px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>Interrupts in Microprocessor 8085&nbsp;</b></p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		There are basically 5 types of interrupts in microprocessor. Different interrupts have different priority.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>\r\n			INTR</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			RST 5.5</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			RST 6.5</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			RST 7.5</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			TRAP</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n</div>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>INTR</b>: It is a 8080A maskable compatible interrupt. Whenever this interrupt comes then usually one of the below mentioned instructions are executed.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		(a)&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Call Instruction</strong>: It is an instruction of 3 bytes.&nbsp; In this case a subroutine is called by the processor and its address is mentioned in the second and third byte of the instruction.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		(b )&nbsp;<strong>RST Instruction</strong>&nbsp;: There are basically 8 RST instructions. These are from (RST<sub>0</sub>&nbsp;&ndash; RST<sub>7)</sub>.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		In this case the value of the current program counter is first saved into the stack then it branches to the memory location N*8 (where N is a 3 bit number from 0 to 7 supplies with the RST instruction.)</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>RST5.5&nbsp;</b>: All the interrupts are maskable interrupts except one i.e. TRAP. It is a maskable interrupt. When this interrupt occurs then the processor saves the contents of the program counter register into stack then it branches to the 2Ch (hexadecimal) address.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>RST6.5</b>&nbsp;is also a maskable interrupt. During this interrupt the processor saves the contents of the program counter register onto stack and then branches to 34h (hexadecimal) address.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;Another type of maskable interrupt is&nbsp;<b>RST7.5.&nbsp;</b>During this interrupt the contents of the program counter are stored onto stack then the branching to &nbsp;3Ch (hexadecimal) address occurs..</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>TRAP :&nbsp;</b>Last interrupt is known as TRAP. It is a non maskable interrupt. In this case after saving the contents of PC register onto stack the branching to the hexadecimal address 24h takes place.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	We have the ability to enable and disable these interrupts by using the DI and EI instructions. Another type of instruction is SIM instruction , The interrupts RST 5.5,&nbsp; RST 6.5 and RST 7.5 can also be enabled and disabled using the SIM instruction.</p>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>Registers used in 8085 Microprocessor</b></p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Registers used in 8085 microprocessor are shown below:</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Flags</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Accumulator</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			General Registers</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Stack Pointer</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Program Counter</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n</div>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>Flag</b>: These are 8 bit registers. There are five types of flags available and each flag is capable of storing a single bit.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Zero &ndash; sets the flag if the result is zero.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Sign &ndash; This flag is set only in the case when the most significant bit of the result is set.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;Auxiliary carry &ndash; Only work in case a carry is generated out from bit 3 to bit 4 of the result</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Parity - This flag is set if the no of bits in the result is even.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;Carry &ndash; If in case a carry is generated while during addition, or borrow or during any other operation like subtraction/comparison then this flag is set.</p>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>Accumulator Registers</b>: Accumulator registers are 8bit registers. All the basic operations like Input/Output, Arithmetic operations and load/store operations are performed using the</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Stack pointer&nbsp;</b>It is a 16 bit register. This register&rsquo;s value is incremented as well as decremented by 2 always.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Program Counter</b>: It is a 16 bit register and it contains the address of the next instruction to be executed.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>General registers</b>: &nbsp;Basically in General register category the following registers are considered. These are : B, C, D, E, F, H, and L registers. These registers can be used &nbsp;individually as well. These all are 8 bit registers. When these combine with each other then after combining these become 16 bit registers. 3 combinations are generally used. BC, DE, and HL.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;When both the D and E registers are used in pairs then the register E contains the lower order bits and in BC register register C is having the lower order bits. DE and BC register pairs can sometimes be used as a Data pointer. The HL pair contains a data pointer. Its basic function is to refer to memory addresses. In this pair register L contains lower order bits.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;8-bit D and 8-bit E registers can be used as one 16-bit DE register pair. When used as a pair the E register contains low-order byte. Some instructions may use DE register as a data pointer.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	8-bit B and 8-bit C registers can be used as one 16-bit BC register pair. When used as a pair the C register contains low-order byte. Some instructions may use BC register as a data pointer.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	8-bit H and 8-bit L registers can be used as one 16-bit HL register pair. When used as a pair the L register contains low-order byte. HL register usually contains a data pointer used to reference memory addresses.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Instruction Set used in Microprocessor 8085</b></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Instructions used in the instruction set of 8085 are given below:</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&bull; Arithmetic Instructions- These instructions handle with the basic functions i.e. add, subtract, increment and decrement.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There are also some Data moving instructions available.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Instructions used to perform some Logical operations like &ndash; OR, AND, XOR and rotate.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Instructions that are used to transfer control from one place to other are : conditional, unconditional, call subroutine, return from subroutine and restarts.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Input/Output instructions.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Some other instructions like - setting/clearing flag bits, enabling/disabling interrupts, stack operations, etc. are also there.</p>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		Intel 8085 uses the following</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<strong>Addressing modes of Microprocessor 8085</strong></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Direct Addressing Mode</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Immediate Addressing Mode</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Implicit Addressing Mode</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Register Addressing Mode</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Register Indirect Addressing Mode</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>1. Direct Addressing Mode</b>&nbsp;: In this mode, the address of the operand is given in the instruction itself.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Suppose we want to run this instruction&nbsp;<b>LDA 2500 H.&nbsp;</b>This will load the contents of memory location 2500 H in accumulator.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		2500 H is the address of source.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Accumulator is the destination register.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>2. Register Addressing Mode</b></p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		In this mode, the operand is in general purpose register.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>MOV A, B -</b>&nbsp;This instruction will move the contents of register B to A.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Where MOV is the operation, B is the source of data and &nbsp;A is the destination.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>3. Register Indirect Addressing Mode</b></p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		In this mode, the address of operand is specified by a register pair.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>MOV A, M</b>&nbsp;&ndash; This instruction will move data from memory location specified by H-L pair to accumulator</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		In the above statement MOV is the operation, M is the memory location specified by H-L register pair, and&nbsp; A is the destination..</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>4. Immediate Addressing Mode</b></p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		In this mode, the operand is specified within the instruction itself.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>MVI A, 05 H</b>- This instruction will &nbsp;Move 05 H in accumulator.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		In the above instruction MVI is the operation, &nbsp;05 H is the immediate data (source) and &nbsp;A is the destination.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<b>5. Implicit Addressing Mode</b></p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		If address of source of data as well as address of destination of result is fixed, then there is no need to give any operand along with the instruction.</p>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>CMA</b>&nbsp;- Complement accumulator.</p>\r\n		<p>\r\n			The above instruction complements the contents of the Accumulator, In the above instruction the source and destination register is A i.e Accumulator itself.</p>\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '27ce9-pin-diagram-of-microprocessor-8085.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-09 10:23:14', 0),
(69, 'Kirchhoff law', 'First law (law of change) :- According to this law the algebraic sum of the various currents at the junction is always 0.', 'Kirchhoff circuit laws, Kirchhoff Current Law, Kirchhoff voltage law, Kirchhoff''s Laws, What is Kirchoff voltage law, What is Kirchoff''s law, What is loop rule', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Kirchhoff law', 'kirchhoff-law', '<div>\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<div style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n		<b>First law</b>&nbsp;(law of change) :- According to this law the algebraic sum of the various currents at the junction is always 0.</div>\r\n	<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n		i.e. I<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;+ I<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;+ I<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;+ &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;. = 0<br />\r\n		OR<br />\r\n		<sup>n</sup>&Sigma;<sub>i=1</sub>&nbsp;I<sub>i</sub>&nbsp;= 0<br />\r\n		I<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;; I<sub>2</sub>; I<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;are coming towards the junction and I<sub>4</sub>&nbsp;; I<sub>5</sub>&nbsp;release from the junction.</p>\r\n	<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n		<img alt="kirchhoffs-law" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/6916f-kirchhoffs-law.jpg" style="width: 320px; height: 273px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<b>Sign convention of Kirchhoff&rsquo;s law:</b><br />\r\n	The current which is coming towards the junction is always +ve and the current which leaves the junction is always -ve.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<b>&nbsp;Second law</b>&nbsp;(junction loop rule) :- According to this law the sum of the potential difference in a closed path of a given circuit is always 0.<br />\r\n	i.e.&nbsp;<sup>n</sup>&Sigma;<sub>i=1</sub>&nbsp;V<sub>i</sub>&nbsp;= 0<br />\r\n	[bcoz in a closed path there is no battery]<br />\r\n	So, according to second law<br />\r\n	0 = I<sub>1</sub>R<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;+ I<sub>2</sub>R<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;+ I<sub>3</sub>R<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;+ &hellip;&hellip;..<br />\r\n	OR</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	0 = V<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;+ V<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;+ V<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;+ &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;<br />\r\n	OR<br />\r\n	Def. =&gt; The sum of the emf&rsquo;s is always equal to sum of the product of current and resistance across each branch of the circuit.<br />\r\n	&xi;<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;+ &xi;<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;+ &hellip;&hellip;.. = I<sub>1</sub>R<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;+ I<sub>2</sub>R<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;+ I<sub>3</sub>R<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;+ &hellip;&hellip;..</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<b>Sign convention:</b><br />\r\n	i. During the looping in clockwise and anti-clockwise direction if the negative terminal of the battery comes first then emf is taken as +ve otherwise it&rsquo;s -ve.</p>\r\n<div style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	ii. During the looping in clockwise or anticlockwise direction if the direction of current is same as of looping then current is taken as +ve otherwise -ve.</div>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	Eg:-</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<img alt="Kirchhoff-law" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/f1003-kirchhoffs-law-1.jpg" style="width: 400px; height: 326px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	i. Mesh or loop<br />\r\n	A =&gt; B =&gt; D =&gt; A<br />\r\n	0 = I<sub>1</sub>P + I<sub>g</sub>G &ndash; (I - I<sub>1</sub>)R</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	ii. Mesh or loop<br />\r\n	A =&gt; D =&gt; C =&gt; E =&gt; A<br />\r\n	&xi; = (I - I<sub>1</sub>)R + (I - I<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;+ I<sub>g</sub>)</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	iii. Mesh or loop<br />\r\n	A =&gt; B =&gt; C =&gt; D =&gt; A<br />\r\n	0 = I<sub>1</sub>P + (I<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;- I<sub>g</sub>)Q &ndash; (I - I<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;+ I<sub>g</sub>) &ndash; (I - I<sub>1</sub>)R</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-10 09:32:51', 0),
(70, 'What is Electric Charge?', 'It is the feature of the sub atomic particles by which we can measure the electromagnetic interaction between the particles. All the objects basically are neutral because most of them have equal amount of positive as well as negative charge', 'Electric charge and force', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'What is Electric Charge?', 'what-is-electric-charge', '<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">It is the feature of the sub atomic particles by which we can measure the electromagnetic interaction between the particles. All the objects basically are neutral because most of them have equal amount of positive as well as negative charge. Due to this charge balancing a huge amount of charge on an object is almost hidden. In simple words we can also write that there is no net charge on an object.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">Types of Charges</strong></p>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		There are two types of charges. One is negative and the other one is positive charge. e.g.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Case 1: Take a silk cloth and a glass rod. Rub the glass rod with the cloth. Now hang that charged rod. Now repeat the same process with another glass rod. Now bring both rods near to each other. You will see that repulsion will take place between the rods.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Case 2: Similar is the case of ebonite rods. Rub two ebonite rods with fur. When we will bring the ends of the rods nearer to each other then they will also show repulsion.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Case 3: Now take a glass rod and rub it with silk cloth. On the other hand took an ebonite rod and rub it with fur. Now bring the ends of both the rods nearer to each other. You will observe that the ends will be start attracting each other.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Now the concept of charges is clear in our minds to some extent. We have seen that the charge present on the glass rod is different from the charge present on the ebonite rod. So, it is clear from this that two types of charges exist in nature. So, it is considered that the charge present on the ebonite rod is negative and on the glass rod is positive. Now it is also proved that unlike charges attract each other and vice versa.</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<span data-mce-style="color: #ff0000;" style="color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Special Key Note</span>: The phenomenon of attraction is not possible in case of unlike charges. Other cases in which the attraction can be possible are:</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Two bodies one is fully charged but the other having no charge will show attraction.</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			An uncharged body when comes in contact with a neutral body will show attraction.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n</div>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		<strong>Different types of objects possess different types of charges</strong></p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Objects having Negative charge<b>:</b>&nbsp;Ebonite rod, plastic seat, Silk cloth, Rubber shoes, Cloth, comb.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Objects having Positive Charge<b>:&nbsp;</b>Glass rod, Fur, Woolen coat, Dry hair, Woolen carpet, Nylon.</p>\r\n', 'c9d14-electric-charge.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-10 09:43:04', 0),
(71, 'Stack and its Operations in Microprocessor', 'The meaning of the word stack is pile or heap. The simplest way to implement a stack in memory is by using an array. In the study of microprocessor, it is basically defined as the group of memory locations, used for the temporary storage of data', 'Stack in microprocessor 8085,What is stack operation in 8085 microprocessor', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Stack and its Operations in Microprocessor', 'stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor', '<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The meaning of the word stack is pile or heap. The simplest way to implement a stack in memory is by using an array. In the study of microprocessor, it is basically defined as the group of memory locations, used for the temporary storage of data. It&rsquo;s functioning consist of basically two phases i.e. reading &nbsp;and writing memory. &nbsp;It used the stack memory whenever there is a need to save the contents of program counter during the process of execution of subroutines. Basically we can apply only two operations on stack.</p>\r\n<ol data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Push</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Pop</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/f3458-stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor.jpg"><img alt="stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/f3458-stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 308px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a> <span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">PUSH operation does the task of saving the contents of the register pair on stack memory and POP operation retrieves back or deletes the contents of stack memory.</span></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	User keeps the sets of memories separately for data storage. So, the name given to these memories is called stack memory. The last memory location of stack is known as TOP.&nbsp; A special register known as Stack pointer is used to store the value of stack top. It is a 16 bit register.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The functioning of stack is basically on the principle of LIFO i.e. Last in First Out.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Stack and its Operations&nbsp;are given below:</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	PUSH Operation: During each Push operation the contents of the stack pointer are decremented by 2 Let us consider that in the register pair following information is stored.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Assume the present contents of the register pair DE are 2070H. The Stack pointer is pointing at location 3000H. On performing the PUSH operation the stack pointer contents are decremented by 1 internally and the address will be reduced to 2FFFH. At the same time the MSB (Most significant bit contents of register D ae stored in the stack memory location 2FFFH as shown below in the figure .</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/80c43-stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor-1.jpg"><img alt="stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/80c43-stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor-1.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 289px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Internally again the contents of the stack pointer are decremented by 1 and it will be reduced to 2FFEH</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	As shown in figure below.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/9d44a-stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor-2.jpg"><img alt="stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/9d44a-stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor-2.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 289px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a>At the same time the contents of the LSB register E are stored in the Stack Memory Location 2FFFH.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	POP Operation: POP operation is reciprocal of push operation. In POP Operation the data from the stack memory is retrieved or received back in the register pair from which it was first saved from the stack memory. When POP operation took place then the contents on the stack top(2FFEH) &nbsp;i.e. 70H are stored back in E register. &nbsp;After this operation the contents of the back stack pointer are incremented by register E and the stack pointer will be 2FFFH.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Then the contents of the stack memory location 2FFFH=20H are stored back in register D.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Internally their will be an increment of 1 to the contents of the stack pointer and the new contents of stack pointer will be incremented by 2 i.e. SP +2 Diagram is shown below:</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<a href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/960ff-stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor-3.jpg"><img alt="stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/960ff-stack-and-its-operations-in-microprocessor-3.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 289px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /> </a></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-10 10:03:39', 0),
(72, 'Delete Himachi Network Connection', 'Delete Himachi Network Connection 1. Right Click on the himachi Network connection. 2. Click on properties. 3. Click on Configure. 4. Then click on Drivers tab.', '', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Delete Himachi Network Connection', 'delete-himachi-network-connection', '<p>\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Delete Himachi Network Connection</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">1. Right Click on the himachi Network connection.</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">2. Click on properties.</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">3. Click on Configure.</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">4. Then click on Drivers tab.</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">5. Then Press the uninstall button.</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">6. All Done</span></p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-15 09:44:09', 0),
(73, 'Conservation of Electric charge', 'The meaning of Conservation of Electric Charge is that charge can neither be created nor destroyed in separation. But in other words we can say that charges can be destroyed as well as created only when they are in opposite and same pairs.', 'Conservation of charge', 'Gurpreet SIngh', 'Conservation of Electric charge', 'conservation-of-electric-charge', '<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	The meaning of Conservation of Electric Charge is that charge can neither be created nor destroyed in separation. But in other words we can say that charges can be destroyed as well as created only when they are in opposite and same pairs. Let&rsquo;s consider the example of rubbing two bodies with each other. When we run the bodies they no new charges are created and no charge is destroyed. The charges are only transferred from one body to another, by changing the electrical neutrality of the bodies.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	Here are some concepts which show the Conservation of Electric Charge.</p>\r\n<ol style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		In all the cases the charge no remains same every time.</li>\r\n	<li style="box-sizing: border-box;">\r\n		In case of pair generation, a gamma photon is divided into a positron and electron. Then the total charge calculated becomes &ndash;e + e=0. So, we can say that the total charge present on a photon is zero.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Electric charge is addictive or not?</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The total amount of charge present on a body is the sum (Algebraic) of the total no of charges present anywhere on the body. But one should be very careful while calculating the algebraic sum. The signs of the charges must be taken into account. Let&rsquo;s take an example to clear this concept of algebraic sum. Suppose we are having three different charges i.e. +q, +2q, -q. Now when we add +2q and &ndash;q then the resultant charge will be +q.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	But if we add +q and +2q then the net charge will be +3q. Hence, it shows the addictive nature of charges.</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-15 09:45:38', 0);
