(74, 'Relation of internal resistance ', 'Consider a cell of resistance ‘R’, a cell of e.m.f. ‘ξ’ having internal resistance ‘r’ connected to the voltmeter and key as shown in fig.', 'emf and internal resistance', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Relation of internal resistance', 'relation-of-internal-resistance', '<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Consider a cell of resistance &lsquo;R&rsquo;, a cell of e.m.f. &lsquo;&xi;&rsquo; having internal resistance &lsquo;r&rsquo; connected to the voltmeter and key as shown in fig.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;"><img alt="" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/6728c-relation-of-internal-resistance.jpg" style="width: 313px; height: 230px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Total resistance of circuit = R + r</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">If I is the current in the circuit then, I = Total e.m.f./Total resistance</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">I = &xi;/r+R &hellip;&hellip;..(1) [bcoz V=RI]</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Acc. To ohm&rsquo;s law:</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">If V is the terminal potential difference across the resistance when circuit is closed then</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">V = I.R</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">V = &xi;/r+R . (R) [from (1)]</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Vr + VR = &xi;R</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Vr = &xi;R &ndash; VR</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Vr = R(&xi;-V)</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">r = (&xi;-V)/V .(R)</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Note : The terminal potential difference at any time is given by</span><br style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;" />\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">V = &xi;-IRr</span></p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-15 09:51:21', 0),
(75, 'How to get IP Address of any website using Python', 'The python script displays the IP Address of any website.', 'python, get ip address of website, find ip address of any website using python', 'Gagandeep Singh', 'How to get IP address of any website using Python?', 'how-to-get-ip-address-of-any-website-using-python', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Following is the script that displayes the IP address of any website :</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	import socket<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	def get_remote_machine_info():<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; remote_host=&#39;www.iowiki.com&#39;<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; try:<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print &quot;IP address: %s&quot; %socket.gethostbyname(remote_host)<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; except socket.error, err_msg:<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print &quot;%s: %s&quot; %(remote_host, err_msg)<br />\r\n	if __name__ == &#39;__main__&#39;:<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; get_remote_machine_info()</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Output is shown below :</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="Get the IP Address of website using python script" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/cb2cd-get_ip_of_website_python_script_iowiki.png" style="width: 262px; height: 62px; margin: 20px;" /></p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-16 11:10:25', 0),
(76, 'Explain various Applications of Laser', 'Communication: – Long distance telephone calls can be made using lasers.  Engineering: – Laser beams can be used for welding purposes.  Surgery: – Lasers can be used by doctors to perform retinal operations.', 'applications of laser', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Explain various Applications of Laser', 'explain-various-applications-of-laser', '<h3 style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	Various applications of laser are :</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/7408a-applications-of-laser.jpg" class="fancybox"><img alt="" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/7408a-applications-of-laser.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 214px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a>\r\n</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Communication</strong>: &ndash; Long distance telephone calls can be made using lasers.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Engineering</strong>: &ndash; Laser beams can be used for welding purposes.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Surgery</strong>: &ndash; Lasers can be used by doctors to perform retinal operations.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Industry</strong>: &ndash;Laser can be used for hard drilling purposes such as Drilling diamond, Drilling in hard steel etc.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<b>Weather forecasting</b>: &ndash; Laser technology can be used in weather forecasting. Lidar is a device which is totally based on laser technology and helps in weather forecasting.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Computers</strong>:-&nbsp; A computer experts are trying to shift the whole computer memory data from one pc to another using laser technology.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Military</strong>:- Powerful war weapons are created by using laser technology.</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-17 08:51:05', 0),
(77, 'Memory space I/O methods', 'In 8085 microprocessor, there are 16 address lines and it is possible to generate 64K bytes of address. Its addressing range is 0000H to FFFFH the possible set of address is called memory space. The addresses are assigned to the memory devices or I/O devi', '', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Memory space I/O methods', 'memory-space-io-methods', '<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Memory space I/O methods:</b>&nbsp;In 8085 microprocessor, there are 16 address lines and it is possible to generate 64K bytes of address. Its addressing range is 0000H to FFFFH the possible set of address is called memory space. The addresses are assigned to the memory devices or I/O devices. There are two different techniques used for assigning addresses to the memory and I/o devices:</p>\r\n<ol data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Memory mapped input/ output method</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Input / Output (I/O) mapped input/ output method</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/91dba-memory-space-io-methods.jpg"><img alt="" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/91dba-memory-space-io-methods.jpg" style="width: 250px; height: 194px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<b style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">Memory Mapped Input /output Method</b><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">: In 8085 microprocessor the possible memory space is 64K byte and its range is 0000 H to FFFF H.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/20618-memory-space-io-methods-1.jpg"><img alt="" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/20618-memory-space-io-methods-1.jpg" style="width: 347px; height: 355px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">In memory mapped input/output method. Some of the available memory spaces are assigned to the memory devices and the remaining are assigned to the input /output devices. In this case once an address is assigned to a memory device the same address cannot be assigned to an input /output device. In this case an input output device is also treated as an memory device. Consider, addresses assigned to the locations are 2000 H to 200 H. Now the addresses which have not been assigned to memory location can be assigned to input/output devices. E.g. 2801 H , 2802 H etc address can be assigned to input/output devices.</span></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	In memory mapped input/output method, the instruction used for the data transfer between a memory device and accumulator are as that are used for data transfer between an input/output device and accumulator. The address of memory and input/output device is contained by specific register pair H-L.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Input/Output mapped input/output method:&nbsp;</b>&nbsp;In this case address assigned to the memory devices can also be assigned to the input/output devices.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	To distinguish that data(address) on the address bus is meant for a memory or an input/output device is decided by the pin IO/M. Basically the IO/M pin indicates whether the Read/Write is to memory or l/O . When pin IO/M&nbsp; is high, the address on the address bus is meant for I/O device. But when the IO/M is low this means that the address bus&nbsp; is meant for the memory device</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-17 09:12:24', 0),
(78, 'What is Electrostatics', 'Electrostatics is the study of charges at rest. It is also named as ‘Static Electricity’. An experiment was conducted in 600BC by a Greek philosopher named ‘Thales’. He rubbed a piece of amber with a cloth made of wool.', 'Applications of Electrostatics, Electrostatics', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'What is Electrostatics', 'what-is-electrostatics', '<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;"><strong>Electrostatics </strong>is the study of charges at rest. It is also named as &lsquo;<strong>Static Electricity</strong>&rsquo;. An experiment was conducted in 600BC by a Greek philosopher named &lsquo;Thales&rsquo;. He rubbed a piece of amber with a cloth made of wool. He observed that the Amber piece gets charged and immediately it started attracting the small pieces of paper, some dust particles, corks etc. Now a question arises that what is amber?</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">Amber is basically a translucent substance which is yellowish brown in color. It is mostly found along the seacoasts. Some of the jewelers also use it in some jewelry items. &lsquo;<strong>Electrum</strong>&rsquo; is the<strong> Greek name</strong> of <strong>Amber</strong>. It name is generated from the words like electric field, electric charge, electric force, electricity, electron, etc.</span></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	1600AD a book was published by William Gilbert called &lsquo; De magento&rsquo;. He assigned a unique name to Amber like substances i.e. &lsquo;Electrica&rsquo;. This name was for all those bodies which started attracting the small objects after got rubbed with a certain substance. At the end, after completing all his experiments on Frictional Electricity, he give the name &lsquo;Resinous&rsquo; to the charge present on the piece of Amber. Amber belongs to Resin category that&rsquo;s why its charge was named so.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	After the passage of time Franklin proposed a new theory. This theory tells us about the nature of the charges. I.e. The wool is positively charged and the charge present on the piece of amber is negative. His theory was absolutely correct. Still we are following this theory.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Frictional Electricity is the other name given to it. It is so called because when we rub two non-insulating bodies with each other then, the charges are generated on both the bodies due to friction.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Eg. When silk cloth and a glass rod both are rubbed with each other then the glass rod is charged or we can say that the glass rod is &lsquo;Electrified.&rsquo;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<img alt="what-is-electrostatics" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/c9d14-electric-charge.jpg" style="width: 373px; height: 169px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	A very common example that will clear the concept is of Plastic Comb which we use daily to comb our hairs. When we pass the comb through dry hair then it gets electrified. Then it starts attracting the small pieces of paper.</p>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n		<strong>Applications of Electrostatics</strong></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n		Van de Graff generator is the most common example. These are designed on the basis of the principle of Electrostatics.</p>\r\n	<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n		Microphones and Loudspeakers also work on this principle.&nbsp;<span style="line-height: 23.8px;">Separation of fly ash to make the environment pollution free</span></p>\r\n	<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n		Inkjet printers&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n		Used in Spraying the paint, power as well as some other substances.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '9768f-what-is-electrostatics.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-19 10:07:02', 0),
(79, 'Carpentry Shop Jobs', 'Material for job:- Soft wood Tools used:- Bench vice, rip saw, marking gauge, steel rule, pencil, try square, Job:- To make a half lap joint', 'Make a half lap joint, Precautions while making half lap joint, Tools used in making half lap joints', 'Karanbir Singh', 'Carpentry Shop Jobs', 'carpentry-shop-jobs', '<h3 style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>JOB-1</b></h3>\r\n<h3 style="box-sizing: border-box; font-family: ''Roboto Slab'', serif; line-height: 1.1; color: rgb(218, 68, 83); margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 20px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Objective&nbsp;</strong><span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">&ndash; Cutting Practice</span></h3>\r\n<h3 style="box-sizing: border-box; font-family: ''Roboto Slab'', serif; line-height: 1.1; color: rgb(218, 68, 83); margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 20px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">Material for job</strong><span style="color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px;">:- Soft wood</span></h3>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>Tools used</strong>:- Bench vice, rip saw, marking gauge, steel rule, pencil, try square,</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Job</b>:- To make a half lap joint</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<img alt="carpentary-shop-jobs" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/22020-carpentry-shop-jobs.jpg" style="width: 252px; height: 182px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Operations done</span></div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		Marking:- marking of job with help of marking gauge and steel rule is done</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		Cutting:- Cutting of work piece according to marking with help of saw</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n			<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Precautions</span></p>\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		1. While cutting make sure to move saw straight keeping in mind that carpenter&rsquo;s saw do cutting in forword stroke</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		2. Hold the work piece or job in vice firmly.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		3. Blunt tools should not be used.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		4. Wooden piece should be free from defects.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		5. Properly seasoned wooden piece should be used.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		6. Always wear shoes while working on workshop floor.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		7. Avoid loose clothing.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		8. Only necessary tools should be present on the working table.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		9. Operate machine in presence of supervisor in proper guidance.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		10. Plane the wood only in direction of grains.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		11. Always wear protective clothing while working on shop floor.</div>\r\n	<h3>\r\n		<b>JOB-2</b></h3>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n			Object:- Paining practice</div>\r\n		<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n			Tools used:- Carpenter&rsquo;s bench, Jack plane, smooth plane</div>\r\n		<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n			<img alt="carpentry-shop-jobs" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/7d85a-carpentry-shop-jobs.jpg" style="width: 314px; height: 218px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></div>\r\n		<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Operations done</span></div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				1 Cutting:- Work piece is taken and cut according to size</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				2 Planning:- The cut work piece is planed using jack plane</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				3 Checking:- After planning the work piece is checked for straightness with help of try square and if not planning operation is repeated</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				<br style="box-sizing: border-box;" />\r\n				<br style="box-sizing: border-box;" />\r\n				<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Precautions</span></div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				1. While cutting make sure to move saw straight keeping in mind that carpenter&rsquo;s saw do cutting in backward stroke.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				2. Hold the work piece or job in vice firmly.<br style="box-sizing: border-box;" />\r\n				3.Blunt tools should not be used.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				4. Wooden piece should be free from defects.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				5. Properly seasoned wooden piece should be used.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				6. Always wear shoes while working on workshop floor.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				7. Avoid loose clothing.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				8. Only necessary tools should be present on the working table.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				9. Operate machine in presence of supervisor in proper guidance.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				10. Plane the wood only in direction of grains.</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				11. Always wear protective clothing while working on shop floor.</div>\r\n			<h3 style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				JOB-3</h3>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				Object:- To make a T joint</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				Tools used:- Bench vice, rip saw, marking gauge, steel rule, pencil, try square, jack plane, firmer chisel, mortise chisel, mallet, smooth plane, sand paper, rasp file</div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				<img alt="carpentry-shop-jobs" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/5542b-carpentry-shop-jobs.jpg" style="width: 506px; height: 340px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></div>\r\n			<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Operations done</span></div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					1 Cutting of raw material:- Cut the wooden piece using rip saw according to the size of job.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					2 Planning:- Smoothen the sides of the job using jack plane, try square.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					3 Marking:- Mark the job according to drawing using marking gauge, try square, pencil and steel rule.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					4 Cutting and chiseling:- Cut the job pieces according to drawing using firmer chisel, mortise chisel, mallet and rip saw</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					5 Assembling and finishing:- assemble the cut pieces with help of mallet and finish the joint using smooth plane, rasp file and sand paper to form half lap joint.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n						<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Precautions</span></p>\r\n				</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					1. Hold the work piece or job in vice firmly.<br style="box-sizing: border-box;" />\r\n					2. Blunt tools should not be used.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					3. Wooden piece should be free from defects.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					4. Properly seasoned wooden piece should be used.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					5. Always wear shoes while working on workshop floor.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					6. Avoid loose clothing.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					7. Only necessary tools should be present on the working table.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					8. Operate machine in presence of supervisor in proper guidance.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					9. Plane the wood only in direction of grains.</div>\r\n				<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n					10. Always wear protective clothing while working on shop floor.</div>\r\n			</div>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>\r\n	JOB-4</h3>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Object:- To make mortise and tenon joint</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Material:- Soft wood</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Tools used:- Carpenter&rsquo;s vice, rip saw, marking gauge, steel rule, pencil, try square, Jack plane, firmer chisel, mortise chisel, mallet, bench vice, smooth plane, sand paper, rasp file.</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<img alt="carpentry-shop-jobs" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/3b1cc-carpentry-shop-jobs.jpg" style="width: 506px; height: 378px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Operations done</span></div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		1 Cutting of raw material:- Cut the wooden piece using rip saw according to the size of job.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		2 Planning:- Smoothen the sides of the job using jack plane, try square.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		3 Marking:- Mark the job according to drawing using marking gauge, try square, pencil and steel rule.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		4 Cutting and chiseling:- Cut the job pieces according to drawing using firmer chisel, mortise chisel, mallet and rip saw</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		5 Assembling and finishing:- assemble the cut pieces with help of mallet and finish the joint using smooth plane, rasp file and sand paper to form mortise and tenon joint .</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;">\r\n			<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Precautions</span></p>\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		1. Hold the work piece or job in vice firmly.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		2. Blunt tools should not be used.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		3. Wooden piece should be free from defects.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		4. Properly seasoned wooden piece should be used.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		5. Always wear shoes while working on workshop floor.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		6. Avoid loose clothing.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		7. Only necessary tools should be present on the working table.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		8. Operate machine in presence of supervisor in proper guidance.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		9. Plane the wood only in direction of grains.</div>\r\n	<div style="box-sizing: border-box; line-height: 23.8px;">\r\n		10. Always wear protective clothing while working on shop floor.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n', '52c52-carpentry-shop-jobs-1.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-20 05:03:00', 0),
(80, 'Metals, Non-metals and Metalloids', 'Metals:  Metals are placed on the left side of the periodic table. They are good conductor of heat and electricity. Metals have a marvellous feature that they can be drawn into wires and can be hammered into sheets', 'What are metals, what are non metals, what are mettaloids', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Metals, Non-metals and Metalloids', 'metals-non-metals-and-metalloids', '<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Metals</strong>:&nbsp; Metals are placed on the left side of the periodic table. They are good conductor of heat and electricity. Metals have a marvellous feature that they can be drawn into wires and can be hammered into sheets. It means that metals are ductile and malleable.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Non-metals</strong>:&nbsp; Non-metals are placed on the extreme right of the periodic table. There are only 18 Non-metals. At room temperature Non-metals exist in solid and gaseous state except Bromine which is liquid at room temperature. Non-metals do not have a property to conduct heat and electricity. Non-metals are brittle but they are neither malleable nor ductile as metals are.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Metalloids</strong>: The elements which show properties of both Metals and Non-metals are called Metalloids. As we know that metallic character decreases and non-metallic character increases from left to right in a period. This change is not brought out suddenly. The elements coming between metals and non-metals are named as metalloids. The elements silicon, germanium, arsenic are some elements which show properties of both metals and non-metals and are called metalloids.</p>\r\n', '8b181-metals-non-metals-and-mettaloids.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-26 02:45:56', 0),
(81, 'Bresenhams line algorithm', 'The Bresenham algorithm is an incremental algorithm which uses the scan conversion technique. The major benefit of this algorithm is that, it is based only on integer calculations. As we move along the x-axis in unit intervals then at each step choose bet', 'bresenhams line algorithm in computer graphics,  Line Drawing Algorithm,  Program to draw a line using Bresenhams Line algorithm,  The Bresenham Line-Drawing Algorithm  Bresenham Line Drawing Algorithm', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Bresenhams Line algorithm', 'bresenhams-line-algorithm', '<p>\r\n	The Bresenham algorithm is an incremental algorithm which uses the scan conversion technique. The major benefit of this algorithm is that, it is based only on integer calculations. As we move along the x-axis in unit intervals then at each step choose between two different y coordinates.</p>\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class="cpp">\r\n#include<iostream.h><iostream.h>\r\n#include<graphics.h><conio.h>\r\n#include<conio.h><graphics.h>\r\n<math.h>void main()\r\n{\r\nint x1,y1,x2,y2,k=0,i,dx,dy,xi,yi,p;\r\nint gd=DETECT,gm;\r\nclrscr();\r\ncout&lt;&lt;&quot;Enter the starting points:&quot;;\r\ncin&gt;&gt;x1&gt;&gt;y1;\r\ncout&lt;&lt;&quot;Enter the ending points:&quot;;\r\ncin&gt;&gt;x2&gt;&gt;y2;\r\ninitgraph(&amp;gd,&amp;gm,&quot;C:TCBGI&quot;);\r\nputpixel(x1,y1,RED);\r\ndx=x2-x1;\r\ndy=y2-y1;\r\nxi=x1;\r\nyi=y1;\r\np=(2*dy)-dx;\r\nfor(k=1;k&lt;=dx;k++)\r\n{\r\nif(p&lt;0)\r\n{\r\nxi=xi+1;\r\np=p+(2*dy);\r\nputpixel(xi,yi,RED);\r\n}\r\nelse\r\n{\r\nxi=xi+1;\r\nyi=yi+1;\r\np=p+((2*dy)-(2*dx));\r\nputpixel(xi,yi,RED);\r\n}\r\n}\r\ngetch();\r\nclosegraph();\r\n}\r\n</math.h></graphics.h></conio.h></conio.h></graphics.h></iostream.h></iostream.h></code></pre>\r\n', '5b8f6-bresenham-line-algo-prog-4.jpg', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-26 02:56:56', 0);
