(82, 'Classification of Crystalline Solids', 'Ionic Solids: The particles of ionic solids consist of both negative as well as positive ions. Positive and negative ions are also known as Cations and anions. Let’s take an example to clear the concept of anions and cations. Suppose that Na+ and Cl- ar', 'characteristics of covalent solids, Characteristics of Hydrogen Bonded Molecular Solids, Characteristics of Ionic Solids, Characteristics of Metallic solids, Characteristics of Molecular Solids, Characteristics of Non Polar Molecular Solids, Characteristi', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Classification of Crystalline Solids', 'classification-of-crystalline-solids', '<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	There are four categories in which&nbsp;Crystalline solids are classified</p>\r\n<ol data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Ionic Solids</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Molecular Solids</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Metallic Solids</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Covalent Solids</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Ionic Solids</b>: The particles of ionic solids consist of both negative as well as positive ions. Positive and negative ions are also known as Cations and anions. Let&rsquo;s take an example to clear the concept of anions and cations. Suppose that Na<sup>+&nbsp;</sup>and Cl<sup>-</sup>&nbsp;are ions present in common salt i.e. NaCl. These ions are bound together with each other by strong molecular forces. These forces are commonly known as Electrostatic forces of attraction.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Characteristics of Ionic Solids:</p>\r\n<ol data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		They have high melting as well as boiling points. This is due to the presence of strong electrostatic forces between them.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These are easily soluble in polar solvents. If we talk about non polar solvents then these are insoluble.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Ionic solids are very hard because these have strong electrostatic forces of attraction i.e. Ions are packed very strongly.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These are brittle in nature. This brittleness depends upon their geometric pattern.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These act as insulators because they have rigid structure. So, ions are closely packed and are not able to move freely. But if these substances are present in molten state or in aqueous solution then these act as good conductors.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Molecular Solids</b>: These are made up of molecules. Their category division depends upon the type of molecules present in them. These are of three types:</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Non Polar Molecular Solids</strong>- These are crystalline solids. The atoms in these solids are similar to the atoms present in noble gases like (argon, neon, helium etc.). Non-polar molecules are also part of theses solids like H<sub>2</sub>, Cl<sub>2</sub>, CH<sub>4</sub>, I<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;etc. London forces are present between these solids i.e. weak dispersion forces. These forces are similar to that of forces like Van de walls forces.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<a class="fancybox" href="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/394a0-classification-of-crystalline-solids.jpg"><img alt="classification-of-crystalline-solids" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/394a0-classification-of-crystalline-solids.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 212px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /> </a></p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	The&nbsp; example of helium is shown with the help of diagram The diagram shows the dipole induced dipole forces between helium atoms.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The main characteristics of these solids are:</p>\r\n<ul data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		The intermolecular forces are very weak in these solids. That&rsquo;s why these are very soft.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Ions are missing in these solids. That&rsquo;s why they act as insulators.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		As we have discussed above that these solids are soft in nature, Due to this property these have very low melting as well as boiling points.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These are mostly found in liquid or gaseous form at room temperature due to weak intermolecular forces.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>Polar Molecular Solids</strong>: These consist of particles known as Polar Molecules like SO<sub>2</sub>, HCl etc. Dipole-Dipole forces of attraction plays their role in these solids. &nbsp;These are also type of Van der Wall&rsquo;s forces. If compared with London Dispersion forces then these are stronger ones.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<img alt="" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/c2050-classification-of-crystalline-solids.png" style="width: 447px; height: 127px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;">\r\n	Characteristics of Polar Molecular Solids</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;These are poor conductors of electricity</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Having low boiling as well as melting points but higher melting and boiling points than Non polar molecular solids.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Their existence is in liquid or gas form because their melting and boiling points are not so high.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These are soft in nature</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hydrogen Bonded Molecular Solids: In these solids the hydrogen atom is linked with highly electronegative atoms. The electronegative atoms are small in size like O, N, F. So, the examples of the final molecule formed after linkage with hydrogen are H<sub>2</sub>O( Electronegative atom oxygen is linked with hydrogen to form Water), NH<sub>3</sub>(Electronegative atom Nitrogen is linked with hydrogen to form Ammonia). The intermolecular forces in these solids are strong hydrogen bonds. So, there are some little changes in their chracteristics:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;These are non conductors of electricity.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The boiling as well as melting points are high as compared to Non Polar Molecular Solids and Polar Molecular solids.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		At room temperature and under normal pressure these act as soft solids and volatile liquids. (Volatile liquids are those which have the tendency to change into vapor form at room temperature)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>Covalent Solids</strong>: These are also known as network solids. The particles of the covalent solids are basically non metal atoms. These non metal atoms are linked to their adjacent atoms by forming covalent bonds. So, the molecules formed are very large in size. Diamond is an example of Covalent solid in which carbon atoms form covalent bonds with adjacent carbon atoms to form a three dimentional structure. Silicon carbide is also a good example of Covalent solids.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;">\r\n	The main characteristics of covalent solids are shown below:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Due to the presence of strong covalent bonds they have very hard and rigid structure.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;These are bad conductor of electricity.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		High Melting Points.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>Graphite an Exceptional Case:</strong>&nbsp;Graphite also comes under covalent solid category. But it is very soft in nature. On the other hand it is also a good conductor if electricity. Let&rsquo;s clear this concept. If we have a look over the structure of the graphite atom then each carbon atom is linked with three carbon atoms. One carbon atom remains free to move. So, due to the presence of these free carbon atoms it is soft as well as good conductor of electricity. So, the bonding between the layers is not too strong. Layer can easily slip over one another. This property makes it a good solid lubricant.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>Metallic Solids:&nbsp;</strong>These consist of free electrons and metal ions having positive charge. Metal atoms have very low ionization energy. So, they have the tendency to leave their valence electrons very easily. After losing the valence electrons we are left behind with the positively charged ions known as kernels. These electrons are capable to move easily through the whole metal surface. In other words we can also cause metallic solids as the sea of free electrons. In this electron sea each atom contributes and adds one or more electrons. So, electrons are negatively charged. Hence they hold the positive ions together in the metallic solids. This force of attraction which holds both these positive ions as well as electrons is known as covalent bond.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;">\r\n	Characteristics of Metallic solids are shown below:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These have high thermal as well as electrical conductivity. This is due to the presence of free electrons. On passing the current these electrons start moving towards the positive electrode.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		In some special cases some color and lusture effects can be seen. This is also due to the presence of free electrons.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These are ductile as well as malleable.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These have high densities and melting points due to the closely packing of the positive ions in the crystal.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" data-mce-style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 819px; height: 451px;" style="line-height:19px;width:819px;height:451px;">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr data-mce-style="mso-yfti-irow: 0; mso-yfti-firstrow: yes;">\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border: solid windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Types of Solid</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left: none; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Constituent Particles</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left: none; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Type of Bonding&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left: none; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Examples</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left: none; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Electrical Conductivity</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left: none; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Physical Nature</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-left: none; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Melting Point</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr data-mce-style="mso-yfti-irow: 1;">\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-top: none; mso-border-top-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p>\r\n					&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Molecular Solids</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(i)Non Polar</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					&nbsp;(ii) Hydrogen Bonded</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					(iii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Polar</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border-top: none; border-left: none; border-bottom: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-right: solid windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-top-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Molecules</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border-top: none; border-left: none; border-bottom: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-right: solid windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-top-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					London Forces</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Hydrogen Bonding</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Dipole-Dipole Interactions</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border-top: none; border-left: none; border-bottom: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-right: solid windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-top-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					CCl<sub>4</sub>, Ar</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					&nbsp;H<sub>2</sub>O(In Ice Form)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border-top: none; border-left: none; border-bottom: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-right: solid windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-top-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Insulator</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border-top: none; border-left: none; border-bottom: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-right: solid windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-top-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-left-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; mso-border-alt: solid windowtext .5pt; padding: 0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;" style="width:91px;">\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Soft in nature</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Hard</p>\r\n				<p data-mce-style="margin-bottom: .0001pt; line-height: normal;">\r\n					Soft</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td data-mce-style="width: .95in; border-top: none; border-left: none; border-bottom: solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-right: solid windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-top-alt: solid windowtext 