(83, 'Seebeck Effect', 'The process of producing induced emf in a thermocouple when all its junctions are maintain are different temperatures. This is known as Seebeck Effect.', '', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Seebeck Effect', 'seebeck-effect', '<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The process of producing induced emf in a thermocouple when all its junctions are maintain are different temperatures. This is known as Seebeck Effect.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	If we consider the series given below:</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	--&gt;Bi, Ni, Pt, Cu, Au, Ag, Fe, Sb&nbsp; --&gt;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;I the above series the direction of current is from Bi towards Sb.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<b>Main causes of Seebeck Effect</b></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;All the atoms consist of variable no of electrons.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<img alt="seebeck-effect" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/0705e-seebeck-effect.jpg" style="width: 480px; height: 400px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	We know that there is variation in electron count per unit volume in different metals. When we make a direct connection between two metals then the flow of electrons takes place from high to a metal having low value of charge density.(i.e High to low charge transfer). After establishing the connection a potential difference is created. This potential difference is known as Contact potential difference. If the contact potential at both the Junctions (J) will be same then no flow of charge (Electrons) took place.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	If we make one junction hot then and other junction cold then again the electron flow will starts due to the change in contact potential.</p>\r\n<div data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<p>\r\n		In case of Sb and Bi the value of emf is 10<sup>-3</sup>V. The Seebeck effect is reversible here. The word reversible means than if both the hot as well as cold junctions are interchanged then it will also effects the flow of current. The flow of current will also be reversed.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-27 03:12:06', 0),
(84, 'What are Polar Satellites?', 'Polar Satellites revolve in the polar orbit around the earth. Now let’s have a look on polar orbit. The orbit which makes an inclination angle of 900 with the equatorial plane of Earth is called polar orbit', '	Polar Satellite, Polar Satellite Universe, Polar Satellites, Polar Satellites of earth, What are Polar Satellites', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'What are Polar Satellites?', 'what-are-polar-satellites', '<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">Polar Satellites revolve in the polar orbit around the earth. Now let&rsquo;s have a look on polar orbit. The orbit which makes an inclination angle of 900 with the equatorial plane of Earth is called polar orbit. The direction of earth&rsquo;s rotation around its axis is from west to east direction but they go around the earth poles from north to south.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="what-are-polar-satellites" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/3a86f-what-are-polar-satellites.jpg" style="width: 240px; height: 282px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">Polar satellites are at a height of approx. 500km to 800km above the earth&rsquo;s surface. The revolution time of polar satellites is nearly 100 minutes. Everyday a polar satellite crosses the earth a no of times. If we fix a camera on polar satellite then from that we can have the view of only a small strip of earth in single orbit. In other words we can say the polar satellite view the whole earth strip by strip in the whole day. In an extract of the whole article we can say that a polar satellite have the ability to monitor 100% of earth&rsquo;s surface. If we simply calculate then we can say that each place on earth is observed twice by the polar satellite. Polar satellites does the major task of collecting information about clouds, atmosphere and having a special focus on ozone hole over Antarctica. The information collection work done by polar satellites is very helpful in remote sensing and meteorological tasks.</span></p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-27 03:16:39', 0),
(85, 'Memory and Input Output Interfacing', 'Memory and Input Output Interfacing  Interfacing is the process of connecting memory and input/ouput devices with a microprocessor or computer. Fig shows the use of decoders to connect microprocessor-8085 with memory input/ output devices.', 'Input output Interfacing Microprocessor, Input output Interfacing Microprocessor 8085, Memory and I O Interfacing, Memory and Input Output Interfacing, Memory and Input Output Interfacing 8085, Memory Interfacing Microprocessor, Memory Interfacing Micropr', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Memory and Input Output Interfacing', 'memory-and-input-output-interfacing', '<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Memory and Input Output Interfacing</strong></p>\r\n<ol style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Interfacing is the process of connecting memory and input/ouput devices with a microprocessor or computer.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Fig shows the use of decoders to connect microprocessor-8085 with memory input/ output devices.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Some of the address lines of&nbsp; 8085 microprocessor are connected to decoder 1 and decoder 2 shown in figure below to select either a memory chip or an input/output device.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		When pin IO/M=Low(0), decoder(1) is enabled and the required memory chip is selected when pin IO/M = High(2) is enabled and required input/Output is selected.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="memory-and-input-output-interfacing" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/61d2f-memory-and-input-output-interfacing.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 334px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<b>Memory Interfacing</b></p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	The process of connecting a memory device with a microprocessor or computer is called interfacing and the devices used for connecting memory with a microprocessor or computer are interfacing devices.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	The address of a memory location or an input/output device is sent out by microprocessor and corresponding memory or an input/output device is selected by the decoder circuit.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	In the figure below decoder 7415138 decoder and it is a 3X8 decoder i.e. it has 3 input lines and corresponding 8-output lines G<sub>1</sub>, G<sub>2A</sub>&nbsp;and G<sub>2B&nbsp;</sub>&nbsp;are the enable signal of the decoder. i.e. to enable decoder its must that G<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;should be high and G<sub>2A</sub>&nbsp;and G<sub>2B</sub>&nbsp;should be low.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<img alt="memory-and-input-output-interfacing" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/666c6-memory-and-input-output-interfacing.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 310px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	A, B,C are the enable lines and by applying appropriate signal at these lines any of the 8 output lines O<sub>0</sub>&mdash;O<sub>7</sub>&nbsp;can be selected.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	An output lines goes low when it is selected while other output lines remain high at this time.</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-27 03:32:28', 0),
(86, 'Disable Mouse wheel scrolling on Google Maps', 'To Disable Mouse wheel scrolling on Google Maps you have to add the style attribute shown below in your iframe.  style="pointer-events:none; border:0;"', 'Disable Mouse scroll in iframe google maps,  Disable Mouse Wheel in iframe google maps, Disable zoom on page scroll in google maps, Disable zooming on google maps during page scroll', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Disable Mouse wheel scrolling on Google Maps', 'disable-mouse-wheel-scrolling-on-google-maps', '<h4 style="font-stretch: normal; line-height: 18px; font-family: Consolas, Monaco, monospace; color: rgb(51, 51, 51);">\r\n	To Disable Mouse wheel scrolling on Google Maps you have to add the style attribute shown below in your iframe <span style="color:#ff0000;"><strong>style=&quot;pointer-events:none; border:0;&quot;</strong></span></h4>\r\n<p>\r\n	<iframe frameborder="0" height="300" src="https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3540.087495492481!2d153.02746689999998!3d-27.466535299999965!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x6b915a1d2f662eb3%3A0x4f3c5ce2c1aafa48!2sAdelaide+St%2C+Brisbane+QLD+4000!5e0!3m2!1sen!2sau!4v1412077371383" style="pointer-events: none; border: 0;" width="600"></iframe></p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-27 03:45:28', 0);
