(87, 'Pin Diagram of 8085 Microprocessor', '8085 is a 40 pin device. It works on +5v single power supply. The explanation of pin diagram of 8085 microprocessor  is given below: X1 and X2 : These are the terminals connected to an external crystal or RC oscillator. These pins are used to drive intern', '8085 microprocessor pin diagram, diagram of 8085 microprocessor, pin diagram of 8085 microprocessor', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Pin Diagram of 8085 Microprocessor', 'pin-diagram-of-8085-microprocessor', '<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	8085 is a 40 pin device. It works on +5v single power supply. The explanation of pin diagram of 8085 microprocessor&nbsp; is given below:</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<img alt="pin-diagram-of-8085-microprocessor" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/63b91-pin-diagram-of-8085-microprocessor.jpg" style="width: 237px; height: 520px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<ol style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		X<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;and X<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;: These are the terminals connected to an external crystal or RC oscillator. These pins are used to drive internal clock generator which produces suitable clock for the operation of microprocessor.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Reset Out : It is active high signal. It indicates that the CPU is being reset. This signal is used by the microprocessor or CPU to reset the other device connected to it.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Reset In: It is an active low input signal it sets program counter to 00000H, resets interrupt enable and HLDA(Hold Acknowledgement).</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		SID: It sis active high signal and it is used to send data to the microprocessor serially.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		SOD: It is an active high signal and it is used to send data from microprocessor to any other O/P device.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		TRAP, RST7.5, RST 6.5, RST 5.5: These are the interrupts when an interrupt comes microprocessor executes the next instruction from a fixed location in the memory.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		INTR: It is called interrupt request. It is of the lowest priority. The INTR is enabled or disabled. It gets disabled by reset or immediately after an interrupt is accepted.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		INTA: This is active low signal and it is known as interrupt acknowledge. When an interrupt request is accepted then the microprocessor sends interrupt acknowledge INTA.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		AD<sub>0&nbsp;</sub>&ndash;AD<sub>7</sub>&nbsp;: Multiplexed Address /Data Bus: These signals are Bi-directional. These are time multiplexed address and data bus. During 1<sup>st</sup>&nbsp;clock cycle, it acts as a least significant 8 bits of memory address. For 2<sup>nd</sup>&nbsp;and 3<sup>rd</sup>&nbsp;clock cycle, it acts as a data bus.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A<sub>8&nbsp;</sub>to A<sub>15</sub>&nbsp;: These are unidirectional signals which carry the most significant bit i.e. 8 bits of the memory address.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		ALE(Address Latch Enable):This is an O/P signal used to demultiplex the address/data bus. In other words ALE is used to separate AD<sub>0&nbsp;</sub>---AD<sub>7&nbsp;</sub>are addresses and when it is low it indicates that the contents on AD<sub>0</sub>&nbsp;&ndash; AD&nbsp;<sub>7</sub>&nbsp;is data.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		S<sub>1&nbsp;</sub>and S<sub>0</sub>: These are two output status signals generated by microprocessor. These indicates type of operation performed by microprocessor. These operations of 8085 are as follows:</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" data-mce-style="width: 304px; height: 88px;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; width: 304px; height: 88px;">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				S<sub>1</sub></td>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				S<sub>0</sub></td>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				Operation</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				0</td>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				0</td>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				Stop</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				0</td>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				1</td>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				Write</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 8px;" valign="top" width="205">\r\n				1</td>\r\n			<td st