yle="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	14.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Read(RD): It is an active low output control signal. When the signal on this pin is low it indicates that cpu read the data form selected memory or I/O locataion.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	15.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Write(WR): It is an active low O/P control signal. When the signal on this pin is slow it indicates that the CPU will write data in the selected memory or I/O location.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	16.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ready: It is an active high input control signal with the help of this pin microprocessor checks he readiness of I/O device for data transfer. i.e. whether the I/O signal is ready to receive or send data.If the signal on this pin is high, CPU will perform data transfer but if the signal on this pin is low then it will wait till the signal goes high.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	17.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hold and HLDA: Hold is an active high input signal and HLDA is an active high output signal. Signal at hold pin indicates that another device is requesting for the use of address, data and control to other device. HLDA is hold acknowledgement. It indicates microprocessor has received the hold request and will transfer the control of address, data and control bus in the next clock cycle.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	18.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; V<sub>cc</sub>: It is used to provide +5v power supply.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	19.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; GND or Vss: This pin always connected to ground. I.e. &ndash;ve charge.</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-27 09:54:07', 0),
(88, 'Dynamic Ram', 'Dynamic Ram is based on the MOS technology. The fabrication on this chip is done using MOS technology. The Dram uses capacitor to store each bit of data. A transfer device called MOSFET is used. The MOSFET acts as a switch', 'DRAM Chip, Dynamic Ram, Dynamic Random Access Memory, What is DRAM', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Dynamic Ram', 'dynamic-ram', '<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	DRAM is a variant of semiconductor memory But its working is slightly different. &nbsp;Lets Discuss the DRAM Basic Architecture.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Dynamic Ram is based on the MOS technology. The fabrication on this chip is done using MOS technology. The Dram uses capacitor to store each bit of data. A transfer device called MOSFET is used. The MOSFET acts as a switch. By determining the value of charge it is checked that whether the particular bit of memory is logical &ldquo;1&rdquo; or &ldquo;0&rdquo;. If the charge will be present in the capacitor then its value will be set to 1 and vice versa. The basic format of dynamic Ram is very simple. It can be easily fabricated on the chip. That&rsquo;s why it is not very costly.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<img alt="dynamic-ram" src="http://iowiki.com/assets/uploads/files/68294-dynamic-ram.jpg" style="width: 445px; height: 554px; margin: 20px; float: left;" /></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	A dynamic ram cell is connected by two lines. One is called as Word Line and other is called as bit line.&nbsp; Bit line is responsible for reading and writing of data. The above shown figure is just a single cell structure. In the whole chip millions of cell similar to this are fabricated on the chip.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Memories are available in different variants i.e., 256 MB, 512 MB, 2048 MB, etc. &nbsp;A splitting technique is used to split the Dynamic Ram into smaller sub arrays to increase the access speed and hence reduce the accessing time. After splitting the word length and the bit lines are shortened. So, this reduces the accessing time of the individual cells. Let&rsquo;s take an example to clear the concept that how splitting takes place. Suppose we have a Ram chip of 256 MB. We can break it in multiples of 2. Lets break it into 16MB smaller array. Hence sixteen small arrays will be used having size of 16 MB each (16 X 16 =256).</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Lets discuss that how the organization of bits took place. The basic task that the word lines performed is to control the gates of the transfer lines. There is a FET channel. All the bit lines are connected to the FET channel and these lines at the end are connected with the sense amplifiers.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Bit lines are further divided into two categories.</p>\r\n<ol data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Folded Bit Lines</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Open Bit Lines</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-27 09:59:14', 0),
(89, 'Band Model of Metallic Bonding', 'In sodium metal each energy level is capable of holding two electrons. So there will be overlapping of 3s and sp orbitals. After overloapping of the innerorbitals having same energy as well as symmetry, the molecular orbitals formed are completely occupie', 'Band Model of Metallic Bonding, Metallic bonding band model', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Band Model of Metallic Bonding', 'band-model-of-metallic-bonding', '<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	When the atomic orbitals overlap then the molecular orbitals are formed. Band model of Metallic Bonding uses the concept of molecular orbitals.&nbsp; As we know that that when two atoms of hydrogen are overlapped then two hydrogen molecules are formed i.e. H<sub>2&nbsp;</sub>. The energy level of both the orbitals will be different from each other. One will be higher and other one will be having higher energy. The magnitude of the energy levels will differ as we change the nuclear distance between the two atoms.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	In other words we can say that &lsquo;n&rsquo; molecular orbitals will be formed by the overlapping of&nbsp; &lsquo;n&rsquo; atomic orbitals. Overlapping requires some certain conditions. The atomic orbitals should have similar amount of energy and same symmetry.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	If we consider the metal lattice of the sodium metal then it consists of a no of atoms. Due to large no of atoms , the molecular orbital&rsquo;s will also be formed in large number. Hence a continuous energy band will be created with large no of energy levels inside. These energy levels are formed by the overlapping of the atomic orbitals that are havin the same amount of energy and are symmetrical.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	In sodium metal each energy level is capable of holding two electrons. So there will be overlapping of 3s and sp orbitals. After overloapping of the innerorbitals having same energy as well as symmetry, the molecular orbitals formed are completely occupied. They are basically occupied by the inner electrons. There is an energy gap which is present between the valence and inner orbital bands. There is a necessity of the enery gap so that the electrons from the completely filled inner orbitals will not get exicited to the valence energy band. All the bands of the atoms in the lattice have common molecular orbitals, because of the common electrons of all the energy bands . All of them belong to the same lattice. So, in other words we can say that they are completely delocalised.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	If we watch then we will find that their is a single electron in the 3s orbital of sodium metal. As a result only the half of the energy level band is filled by the elctrons . Due to this capability of accepting electrons, sodium metal is a good conductor of electricity. Alkali metals are also good conductor of elctricity. The reason behind their conductivity is same as that of sodium metal.</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-03-31 10:28:36', 0),
(90, 'Explain optical astronomy and radio astronomy?', 'Optical astronomy: In optical astronomy, the heavenly bodies are observed via optical window. Various methods used to study the optical astronomy are:  Refracting telescopes Reflecting telescopes', 'difference between optical astronomy and radio astronomy, differentiate between optical astronomy and radio astronomy, explain optical astronomy and radio astronomy, optical astronomy, optical astronomy and radio astronomy, optical astronomy and radio ast', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Explain optical astronomy and radio astronomy?', 'explain-optical-astronomy-and-radio-astronomy', '<h3 style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	Optical astronomy and Radio astronomy</h3>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Optical astronomy:</strong>&nbsp;In optical astronomy, the heavenly bodies are observed via optical window. Various methods used to study the optical astronomy are:</p>\r\n<ul style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Refracting telescopes</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Reflecting telescopes</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	The dust particles that are present between the universe and the earth restricts the light rays from entering into the telescope.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Radio astronomy:</strong>&nbsp;In radio astronomy, the heavenly bodies are observed via radio window. It makes use of radio telescopes and these are the most commonly used telescopes.</p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Advantages</strong></p>\r\n<ol style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Due to the large aperture of radio telescope, it can easily detect very small radio signals.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		These waves can pass through various types of obstacles such as dust, layers, clouds etc. but on the other side, visible waves cannot.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Radio waves arising from various heavenly bodies are able to reach the earth even if the bodies are present at large distance from the earth.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Radio astronomy makes use of low cost devices.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;Through radio waves, a continuous supervision of the heavenly bodies can be achieved at any moment without concerning whether it is a day or night.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<strong>Disadvantages</strong></p>\r\n<ol style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		The intensity of radio waves gets too low on reaching the earth. Therefore, various sensitive detectors are brought to use in order to detect the radio waves.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Due to the low power radio telescope, overall study of the heavenly bodies is not possible.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		There comes difficulty while distinguishing the radio waves i.e. whether they are coming from the heavenly bodies or being generated from the radio stations present on the earth. The problem arises due to the similarity of frequencies of different radio waves.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		There is a necessity to use the radio telescopes due to the large wavelength of radio waves. On the other hand there is no need to use these type of telescopes in case of visible light.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-04-03 09:36:43', 0),
(91, 'What is the mass and density of the sun?', 'Consider a planet that rotates around the sun with mass m and let T be the time period of its revolution. Let the mass of the sun be M and its radius as R. Relation of the centripetal force is shown as:  m R ω2 = m R (2 π / T) 2 = 4 π2 m R / T2', 'determine the mass and density of the sun, find out the density of sun, find out the mass of the sun, how to calculate density of the sun, how to calculate mass and density of the sun, how to calculate the mass of the sun, how to find density of the sun, ', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'What is the mass and density of the sun?', 'what-is-the-mass-and-density-of-the-sun', '<h3 data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Mass and Density of the sun</h3>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Consider a planet that rotates around the sun with mass m and let T be the time period of its revolution. Let the mass of the sun be M and its radius as R. Relation of the centripetal force is shown as:</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	m R &omega;<sup>2&nbsp;</sup>= m R (2 &pi; / T)&nbsp;<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;= 4 &pi;<sup>2&nbsp;</sup>m R / T<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The gravitational force of the sun applies an extreme pressure on the planet. The relation for the gravitational force is given as:</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	F= G M m / R<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	Such that, G M m / R<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;= 4 &pi;<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;m R / T<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;">\r\n	We get the final relation as,</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	M = 4 &pi;<sup>2M&nbsp;</sup>m R<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;/ G T<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	As per the formula, Mass (weight) = Volume * Density</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	As we have previously considered that the radius of the sun is R and its density is 1.43. Therefore, on substitution we get,</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&rho; = 3 &pi; R<sup>3&nbsp;</sup>/ G T<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;R<sup>3</sup></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Such that from the above relation, the values of&nbsp; M and&nbsp;&rho; can be easily determined.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-04-04 09:51:40', 0),
(92, 'What is Universe?', ' Solar system: The other name of solar system is ‘sun’s family’. All the nine planets rotate around the sun in different orbits, this is because of the center position occupied by the sun.', 'components of Universe, explain galaxies, explain stars, explain Universe, galaxies, name of 9 planets, name of 9 planets in serial order, name of nine planets in serial order, nine planets, parts of Universe, Solar system, stars, universe, Universe physi', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'What is Universe?', 'what-is-universe', '<h3 data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Universe</h3>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	The stars, galaxies, solar system and the empty space present around us combined to form the universe.</p>\r\n<h3 data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Universe comprises of</h3>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>1. Solar system:</strong>&nbsp;The other name of solar system is &lsquo;sun&rsquo;s family&rsquo;. All the nine planets rotate around the sun in different orbits, this is because of the center position occupied by the sun. As the rotation of the planet changes the distance of the planets also varies with respect to sun. When the planets come closer to the sun, they start revolving at a high speed and this motion is controlled by the gravitational pull of the sun. The 9 planets are:</p>\r\n<ul data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Mercury</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Venus</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Earth</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Mars</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Jupiter</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Saturn</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Uranus</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Neptune</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Pluto</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<em>Method to learn the names of all the 9 planets (in serial order):</em></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	&nbsp;<strong>My Very Educated Mother Just Served Us Nine Pizzas.</strong></p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Here, the first alphabet of each word is the starting alphabet of each planet (in serial order).</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>2. Galaxies:</strong>&nbsp;Formation of galaxies is achieved through a combination of gases, stars, dust particles etc with the help of gravitational force. We also live in a galaxy called &lsquo;Milky way&rsquo;. In hindi, milkyway is pronounced as &lsquo;Akashganga&rsquo;. It looks like a pure white strip of light stretched over the sky. This strip of light is visible only in clear night. Sun is also the part of this galaxy. Milky way consists of&nbsp; billions of stars ranging about -10<sup>11</sup>. Other than milky way several other galaxies are also present in the universe with the galaxy count of about 10<sup>11</sup>.</p>\r\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: justify;" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Georgia, ''Times New Roman'', ''Bitstream Charter'', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<strong>3. Stars:</strong>&nbsp;Stars are the heavenly bodies that glow by emitting the light. These are visible only in the clear night i.e. in absence of clouds. The sun is also considered as a star and known as the brighest star. Approximately 2500 stars can be seen at one time on a clear night. Alpha Centauri is also one of the brightest star with an approximate distance of 4.3 light yrs from the earth.</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-04-08 10:53:49', 0),
(93, 'Explain the spectrum of hydrogen?', 'Bohr explained that when an electron jumps from one energy orbit to another energy orbit i.e. say from n=ni to n= nf then energy emission will take place. The energy emitted will be equal to the difference of the energy of the two orbits. These small pack', 'Balmer Series, Bohr Spectrum Of hydrogen Atom, Brackett Series, Explain the spectrum of hydrogen?, Humphrey Series, Lyman Series, Paschen Series, Pfund Series, Spectrum Of Hydrogen', 'Gurpreet Singh', 'Explain the spectrum of hydrogen?', 'explain-the-spectrum-of-hydrogen', '<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Bohr explained that when an electron jumps from one energy orbit to another energy orbit i.e. say from n=n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i&nbsp;</span>to n= n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">f&nbsp;</span>then energy emission will take place. The energy emitted will be equal to the difference of the energy of the two orbits. These small packets are known as photons. As with the transition of the electrons a line is produced in the spectrum. Depending upon the photons different types of spectrum&rsquo;s are formed. Bohr gave the explanation about the spectrum of hydrogen having only one electron. So we can&rsquo;t apply this spectrum to other atoms which consists of more than one electron.&nbsp; Different series are available in the hydrogen atom.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Balmer Series</span>: &ndash; when the&nbsp;electron&nbsp;jumps from any higher stationary orbit to the second stationary orbit with n=2, the spectral lines falls in this category. So, n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>=2</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	W=R<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">H</span>&nbsp;(1/2<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;&ndash; 1/n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>), n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>=3, 4, 5&hellip;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Lyman Series</span>: &ndash; when the&nbsp;electron&nbsp;jumps from any higher stationary orbit to first stationary orbit, the spectral lines falls in the Lyman series. For Lyman series, n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>=1.</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	Now putting n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">f</span>=1 in the relation given by Bohr, w=R<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">H</span>(1/1<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;&ndash; 1/n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>), n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>=2, 3, 4&hellip;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Brackett Series</span>: &ndash; when the&nbsp;electron&nbsp;jumps from any higher stationary orbit to fourth stationary orbit with n=4, the spectral lines fall in this category. So, n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">f</span>=4</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	w= R<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">H</span>&nbsp;(1/4<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;&ndash; 1/n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>), n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>= 5, 6, 7&hellip;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Pfund Series</span>: &ndash; when the&nbsp;electron&nbsp;from any higher stationary orbit jumps to fifth stationary orbit with n=5, the spectral lines falls in this category. So, n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">f</span>=5</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	w= R<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">H</span>&nbsp;(1/5<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;&ndash; 1/n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>), n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>=6, 7, 8&hellip;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Paschen Series</span>: &ndash; when the&nbsp;electron&nbsp;falls from any higher stationary orbit to third stationary orbit with n=3, the spectral lines falls in this category. So n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">f</span>=3</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	w= R<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">H</span>&nbsp;(1/3<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;&ndash; 1/n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>), n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>=4, 5, 6&hellip;</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	<span style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">Humphrey&nbsp;Series</span>: &ndash; when the&nbsp;electron&nbsp;falls from any higher stationary orbit to sixth stationary orbit with n=6, the spectral lines falls in this category. So n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">f</span>=6</p>\r\n<p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px; color: rgb(107, 107, 107); font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 23.8px; text-align: justify;">\r\n	w= R<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">H</span>&nbsp;(1/3<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>&nbsp;&ndash; 1/n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;">2</span>), n<span style="box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;">i</span>=7, 8, 9&hellip;</p>\r\n', '', 'Published', 0, 0, '2016-04-15 06:29:05', 0);
